<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Conservative Promise Tax Cuts in Manifesto </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 2 (Xinhua) -- In a fresh effort to boost his
election campaign, British Prime Minister John Major today
promised to cut income tax, improve public service and curb crimes
if he is elected for another term.
</P>
<P>
Launching his manifesto for the May 1 general election, Major
vowed to cut the basic rate of income tax from 23 percent to 20
percent.
</P>
<P>
"We will remain the lowest taxed economy in Europe and press
toward a 20 percent basic rate of tax," he said.
</P>
<P>
Major, about 20 points behind Labor's Tony Blair, his main
rival, in recent opinion polls, is trying to narrow the gap by
wooing the floating voters who will not make their choice until
the last minute.
</P>
<P>
The manifesto, covering issues from public spending to welfare
reform and education, pledged tax breaks for people who stay at
home to take care of children or the sick.
</P>
<P>
Major also promised to improve public service and continue
tough policies on law and order -- keeping crime falling by tough
penalties for career criminals.
</P>
<P>
"Our goal must be to make Britain the best place in the world
to live," he said. "We are on course to meet my target of doubling
the living standards by 2020."
</P>
<P>
"It is time for change. Time for a change to the next phase of
Conservative prosperity," he added.
</P>
<P>
However, on the thorny issue of Britain's joining the European
single currency, Major was cautious and merely said that a new
Conservative government would not legislate in the first session
of a new parliament on the issue.
</P>
<P>
An opinion poll published in today's Guardian newspaper showed
a four points drop in Labor's lead over the Conservatives compared
with last month's figure, a sign that raised Tories' hope for
further effect of the manifesto.
</P>
<P>
The Conservative party has been racked by split among its
members over European integration and a string of financial and
sexual scandals involving a dozen Conservative legislators.
</P>
<P>
Major began the election campaign on March 17 by announcing May
1 as the voting date, the longest electioneering of this
century. The Labor is also expected to announce its manifesto
today. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
