<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa to Raise Water Price: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 2 (Xinhua) -- The South African government
is considering to raise water price considerably in a bid to curb
the waste of the "scarce commodity", a top official said today.
</P>
<P>
Piet Pretorius, Director of Water Utilization, said water had
to become more expensive as it was a scarce commodity. He warned
that if not managed diligently, water sources in South Africa
would run out by the year 2030.
</P>
<P>
The Department of Water Affairs was reportedly drafting a
white paper on the pricing of water as part of the govenment's
effort to stretch the country's water supplies.
</P>
<P>
"There is no doubt that water will become considerably more
expensive," Pretorius said, adding that the water services bill
would be another measure to preserve the country's water
resources.
</P>
<P>
To be tabled in parliament shortly, Pretorius said, the water
bill proposed a ban on the watering of gardens between 11 AM and
3 PM from October and March. Hosing down a car would also be
prohibited if the bill became law. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
