<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Life Banned Referee to Appeal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVE, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Veteran referee Kurt Rothlisberger
has appealed against the life ban handed to him after European
football's governing body UEFA found him guilty of attempting to
fix a European Champions League match.
</P>
<P>
UEFA announced the news on Wednesday but the date and the venue
of the appeal has yet to be fixed, according to a press report.
</P>
<P>
UEFA said that Rothlisberger had tried to fix the 1996
second-leg tie between French first division side Auxerre and
Swiss champions Grasshopper Zurich. Auxerre had won the first-leg
1-0.
</P>
<P>
UEFA claim Rothlisberger contacted Grasshopper officials two
weeks before the match, saying he was a friend of the Belarus
referee in charge of the match and that if they wanted he could
fix the result.
</P>
<P>
Rothlisberger, one of the world's best known referees and
veteran of more than 1,000 matches, is reported to have demanded
over 60,000 dollars.
</P>
<P>
Grasshopper president Romano Spadaro and club coach Erich Vogel
 immediately contacted UEFA who opened an inquiry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
