<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Controversy Heated Over Russian-Belarusian Union </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 2 (Xinhua) -- While the Kremlin hastened toward
an overall union with Belarus, opposition to a quick integration
with Belarus is mounting in the Russian capital.
</P>
<P>
Russian President Boris Yeltsin and Belarusian President
Alexander Lukashenko today signed a brief document as a basis for
a union between the two former Soviet republics. They also
initialled a more detailed union charter, which is subject to a
month's public debate.
</P>
<P>
Although Belarus seemed eager to get the treaty clinched,
Russian leadership appeared divided over the integration, which
will coordinate the two countries' foreign, economic and defense
policies.
</P>
<P>
Boris Nemtsov, the newly-appointed First Deputy Prime Minister,
on Monday voiced his opposition to the accelerated unification,
saying it should not be rushed along.
</P>
<P>
While acknowledging the treaty was necessary, he said the
merger must not hurt the people of Russia and Belarus
economically, politically or socially, Itar-Tass News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
He said the treaty should have been thoroughly considered
before being signed lest it might create mess afterwards.
</P>
<P>
Echoing him, leader of the liberal Yabloko, Grigory Yavlinsky,
said the time was not ripe for the union.
</P>
<P>
A rushed unification would only worsen the economic and
political situation both in Russia and Belarus, he said, adding
that provisions of the union accord needed revising.
</P>
<P>
However, Speaker of the State Duma (lower house of Russian
parliament) Gennady Seleznyov said on the eve of the signing
ceremony that most legislators back the treaty and the Duma will
most likely ratify it after a debate on April 9.
</P>
<P>
According to Seleznyov, the union is a first step and will be
followed by the creation of a confederation of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the Duma Committee on Legislation and Court Reform,
Anatoly Lukyanov, said today that the union was bound to
materialize in this form or that in spite of the opposition from
some people.
</P>
<P>
He hinted that the move was a step to counter NATO's eastward
enlargement.
</P>
<P>
Speaking before the signing ceremony today, Yeltsin said that
the two countries would retain their sovereignty under the
treaty. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
