<DOCNO> XIE19970403.0010 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-02 16:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Proximity Talks in Cyprus Deal With Substance: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, April 2 (Xinhua) -- The ongoing U.N.-sponsored
proximity talks between the Greek and Turkish Cypriot sides deal
with the substance of the Cyprus problem, a senior Cypriot
government official confirmed here today.
</P>
<P>
The official also said it would be "premature and
irresponsible" to conclude that the talks, conducted by
U.N. Resident Representative Gustave Feissel, have not yielded
any results.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at his daily press briefing, government spokesman
Yiannakis Cassoulides said that "discussions between President
Glafcos Clerides and Feissel cover the substance of the problem
and most of the time is taken up by issues relating to
substantive aspects of the Cyprus question."
</P>
<P>
These discussions are useful, the spokesman said, adding that
"obviously we are talking about good-will gestures."
</P>
<P>
However, Cassoulides declined to speak about progress on the
substance at the proximity talks, abiding by an agreement on not
to disclose the content of the talks.
</P>
<P>
Feissel has shuttled between the two sides and conveyed the
messages from one side to the other twice a week since March 10
when the proximity talks started.
</P>
<P>
The talks are aimed at breaking current deadlock on the Cyprus
 problem and paving the way for the U.N. proposed direct
negotiations between the leaders of the two community on the
island.
</P>
<P>
Cassoulides also refrained from commenting on demands by
Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash that foreign tourists
entering Cyprus from the Turkish occupied northern areas, are
allowed to visit the government controlled areas of the
Republic.
</P>
<P>
"I would not like to comment on such matters because they are
likely to be on the agenda of the proximity talks," he explained,
noting that matters pertaining movement of tourists will depend
on the essence of a settlement.
</P>
<P>
Asked to comment on the conviction of foreign diplomats as
well as Cypriot and Greek officials that direct negotiations are
certain to take place, Cassoulides said "this assessment relies
on the hope that the proximity talks will lead to direct
negotiations in the first half of 1997."
</P>
<P>
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan has announced his
determination to bring the rival leaders Clerides and Denktash
into a direct negotiation table before the end of June this year.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus remains divided since 1974 when Turkish troops
occupied the northern third of the island in the wake of a
short-lived coup seeking union with Greece. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
