<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Factory Orders Up 0.8 Percent in February </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Orders to U.S. factories gained
by a moderate 0.8 percent in February following a strong 2.5
percent gain the month before, U.S. Commerce Department reported
today.
</P>
<P>
The department said that overall factory orders in the month
rose to a seasonally adjusted 325.9 billion dollars, the record
high.
</P>
<P>
A big 7.1 percent gain in orders for communications and other
electronic equipment more than offset a 4.1 percent drop in
transportation equipment.
</P>
<P>
Orders for durable goods, items expected to last for more than
three years, rose by 1.5 percent in February after shooting up 3.8
percent the month before. Non-durable goods orders increased by
0.1 percent after a 0.9 percent gain in January.
</P>
<P>
Orders for capital goods, excluding the volatile military and
transportation sectors, advanced 6.9 percent in February after a
3.1 percent rise a month earlier.
</P>
<P>
Shipments of manufactured goods, a measure of current
production, increased 0.9 percent, the seventh gain in eight
months.
</P>
<P>
The backlog of unfilled orders rose by 0.9 percent, the sixth
consecutive gain. A growing backlog suggests businesses will have
to increase production and perhaps hire more workers to meet
demand.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that today's report fits with recent evidence of
robust growth during the first quarter in most economic sectors in
the country.
</P>
<P>
A report from the U.S. National Association of Purchasing
Managers said Tuesday that manufacturing in the U.S. strengthened
at the fastest pace in more than two years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
