<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 3 S. Leone Journalists Remanded in Custody Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Three editors of the independent
biweekly newspaper, Expo Times were again refused bail when they
appeared before a Freetown magistrate court today.
</P>
<P>
They are facing four counts of spying and possession of a
military document and this is the third time their application
for bail has been turned down since their arrest last month.
</P>
<P>
Magistrate Naomi Tunis adjourned further hearing for Friday.
And the men were taken to the maximum security prison in the
capital.
</P>
<P>
The prosecution said the documents would be useful to the
enemy, or the Revolutionary United Front (RUF) which has waged a
six-year rebel war in the west African state.
</P>
<P>
Justice ministry officials said the case will be transferred
shortly to the high court to try the accused in secret because of
the alleged documents bordering on state security.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Sierra Leone Association of Journalists (SLAJ)
in a press release signed by over 35 editors and addressed to
President Tejan Kabbah, has ''pleaded'' for the three editors to
be set free.
</P>
<P>
It is the first time since independence in 1961 that any
Sierra Leone national has been charged with spying. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
