<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1500 GMT, April 2 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI -- A one-day special session of Sabha (the lower
house of parliament) will be convened on April 11 to allow the
14-party United Front government led by H.D. Deve Gowda to seek a
vote of confidence, it was officially announced here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
BONN -- Germany's current account deficit rose to 9.3 billion
marks (5.6 billion U.S. dollars) in January, more than double the
4.1 billion marks (2.47 billion dollars) registered in January
last year, the German Federal Office of Statistics in Wiesbaden
said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
TOKYO -- Japan's Supreme Court ruled Wednesday that the Ehime
prefectural government's donation of public money to the Yasukuni
Shrine from 1981 to 1986 violates the Constitution which
stipulates the separation of politics and religion.
</P>
<P>
LUSAKA -- Zambia will not send troops to the Zambian-Zairean
border because the military build-up will not auger well in view
of the war situation in the neighboring country, a senior Zambian
military official has said.
</P>
<P>
ISLAMABAD -- There is no shortcut to normalize bilateral
relations between Pakistan and India, a Pakistani Foreign Office
spokesman said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
LONDON - Britain's ruling Conservatives narrowed its gap with
the opposition Labor Party in the latest opinion polls to 14
points, the Guardian newspaper said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
ULAN BATOR -- The recruits of the Mongolian armed forces will
be reduced by 30 percent this year, but the recruits of border
guards will increase by 10 percent, Lieutenant General
Damdinsuren, the chief of general staff, has announced.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Palestinian police have arrested 50 activists from
the militant group Islamic Jihad, which was believed to be behind
at least one of the two suicide bombings in Gaza Strip Tuesday.
</P>
