<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU GDP Growth Slows Down to 1.59 Percent in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, April 2 (Xinhua) -- The European Union's gross
domestic product (GDP) growth in real terms slowed down to 1.59
percent in 1996 from 2.48 percent in the previous year, the EU's
statistical office Eurostat reported today.
</P>
<P>
The figures showed that most EU member states saw slower paces
of growth last year. Exceptions were the Netherlands, Portugal
and Greece, which had higher growth rates than the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The strongest growth was 7.84 percent in Ireland. Although
this was down from the 10.73 percent recorded in 1995, it was
still three times the growth rate of the next highest -- the
Netherlands, and five times the EU average.
</P>
<P>
The weakest growth was Italy's 0.77 percent, compared with 2.97
percent in 1995.
</P>
<P>
All 15 EU member states saw a growth in per capita GDP,
although generally at lower rates than those for GDP itself.
</P>
<P>
The EU's GDP in the fourth quarter last year was estimated to
be 0.29 percent up over the third quarter. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
