<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe to Host African African-American Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's investment drive will
get a major boost in July when an American influential clergyman
Reverend Leon Howard Sullivan brings over a 1,000-strong
broad-based delegation for an African African-American "summit."
</P>
<P>
The four-day summit seeks to create consistency within the
United States in assisting African countries with various forms
of aid.
</P>
<P>
It will be the fourth summit held in Africa.
</P>
<P>
Sullivan told journalists after a meeting with Zimbabwean
President Robert Mugabe today that this year's summit is bound to
be the best so far, describing it as the largest event.
</P>
<P>
''We expect thousands of African-Americans from business
people, doctors, politicians, educationists and other
contingencies from the Caribbean and Europe,'' said Sullivan.
</P>
<P>
''It's not only Zimbabwe which is to benefit, but we are also
targeting other smaller countries that have been shut off
before... We will also deal with democracy, peace and hope to
have up to 25 African leaders,'' said Sullivan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
