<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-02 17:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Vows to Fight Racist Attacks on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Turkish State Minister Lutfu
Esengun said today that the Turkish government would take any
measures against racist attacks on Turkish citizens living in
Germany and in the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
Esengun made the remarks at a press conference in Istanbul,
the largest city of Turkey, before his departure for the
Netherlands and Germany for the investigations into the racist
attacks against Turks in the two states, according to the
semi-official Anatolia News Agency.
</P>
<P>
Four members of a Turkish family died and another was
critically injured after an arson attack in Germany Monday.
</P>
<P>
In another case, six Turkish citizens including five children
died last week after leaping from their third-floor apartment
window when a fire broke out in their 13-story building in the
Hague, the Netherlands. Dutch police suspected that it was a
racial attack.
</P>
<P>
Esengun said that the Turkish people were deeply hurt by the
incidents happened in the above two countries, adding "all these
are the problems of humanity."
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the Turkish government will make
serious investigations into the incidents, saying that taking
measures to prevent the repetition of such incidents is more
important than to find those who were responsible for the
attacks.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Turkish Foreign Ministry Spokesman Omer Akbel today
strongly condemned the arson attacks on Turkish citizens living
in the Netherlands and Germany.
</P>
<P>
He called for the effective measures to be taken to protect the
lives of Turkish citizens living abroad.
</P>
<P>
Over 3.5 million Turkish citizens living abroad and most of
them are living in Germany. 
</P>
</TEXT>
