<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cutting Budget Deficit Urged in Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's Planning Commissioner
Richard Hove has challenged senior civil servants to be
resourceful in coming up with realistic economic measures aimed
at effectively reducing government's budget deficit.
</P>
<P>
Opening a three-day meeting for heads of government ministries
in Nyanga of eastern Zimbabwe today, Hove said Zimbabwe's second
phase of economic reforms must tackle the unfulfilled objectives
of the first phase.
</P>
<P>
He cited examples of unachieved goals of the first phase of
reforms like the huge public enterprise losses and the high
budget deficit.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is examining draft policy documents on the vision
2020 program and the Zimbabwe program for economic and social
transformation.
</P>
<P>
Hove said Zimbabwe's economic performance has improved as a
result of the good rainy season which resulted in real gross
domestic product growth of over eight percent in 1996 and
expectations that in 1997 it would grow by five percent.
</P>
<P>
He expressed fear that such good economic performance may not
be sustainable as it is influenced by the unpredictable weather.
</P>
</TEXT>
