<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philips Finds Partner for Hearing Aids </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Philips Hearing Instruments and
US company Micro-Tech have agreed a strategic alliance which they
hope will set an international standard for digital hearing aids,
the Dutch newspaper Het Financieele Dagblad reported on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper says the US company is to use Philips' micro
chips and the software for its products.
</P>
<P>
"The strategic importance of the deal is also strong," a
Philips spokesman was quoted by the newspaper as saying.
</P>
<P>
"The new chip will give us a jump on the competition and could
become the world standard."
</P>
<P>
Philips, the Dutch electronics giant, and Micro-Tech aim to
present an improved hearing aid this month, according to the
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that both companies would continue to make
their own products, but would work together in their promotion and
distribution.
</P>
<P>
Philips hopes that deal will increase its market share in the
Untied States, but says it is targeting the medical market rather
than consumers.
</P>
<P>
The Philips spokesman said reportedly that the hearing aids
division met the profit targets outlined by Philips president Cor
Boonstra, but declined to give actual profit or turnover figures.
</P>
</TEXT>
