<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Breastfeeding Transmission of HIV Small: Expert </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Consultant paediatrician Rose
Kambarami said here today only five percent of all babies born in
Zimbabwe are at risk of acquiring HIV through breastfeeding.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on ''HIV and Breastfeeding'' at a Harare general
hospital breastfeeding commemoration week, Kambarami said about
120,000 babies out of the 400,000 of contracting the deadly HIV,
while 30 percent of the mothers were HIV positive.
</P>
<P>
She said, ''just because a mother is carrying HIV does not
mean that the baby will definitely get the virus. There is a
50-50 percent chance that the baby will contract the virus.''
</P>
<P>
''Only 60,000 out of the 400,000 babies born every year will
eventually get the infection,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
Kambarami said a third of the 60,000 mothers would infect
their babies during delivery, while another third infected them
during pregnancy, another third of the women would transit HIV to
their babies through breastfeeding.
</P>
<P>
She said Zimbabwe could not abandon the whole initiative of
baby friendly clinics because of the five percent given the
enormous benefits of breastfeeding. 
</P>
</TEXT>
