<DOCNO> XIE19970403.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK House Prices Keep Steady Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 2 (Xinhua) -- House prices in Britain are
continuing to rise, but at a relatively modest pace and there is
no indication of a return to a 1980s-style boom, according to
separate figures published by building society, banks and
insurers.
</P>
<P>
The Halifax Building Society, the country's biggest mortgage
lender, said today that house prices rose by one percent last
month after an 0.6 percent increase in February, the best monthly
figure since December and taking annual price rises to 7.2
percent, compared with 6.8 percent in February.
</P>
<P>
The average house price last month was 67,334 pounds (110
thousand US dollars), the biggest price recorded by the Halifax
since November 1991.
</P>
<P>
However, the building society said that despite the sharp rise
in house prices during March, UK prices are still 4.2 percent
below their peak in May 1989, and latest figures for the number of
property transactions in England and Wales showed a fall of 4.1
percent in February compared with January.
</P>
<P>
UK property market's steady recovery is also shown by insurers
Legal &AMP; General's latest survey and the latest bank lending
figures.
</P>
<P>
Legal &AMP; General's survey of 1,000 people found that, while
housing market activity continues to increase, there are no signs
of the market overheating and the market remains an orderly one.
</P>
<P>
It gave three reasons why the market would remain "orderly".
First, the number planning to move in the next 12 months had
fallen from 26 percent last September to 17 percent. Second,
nearly two-thirds of people expected interest rates to rise and
lastly, there is the uncertainty caused by the May 1 general
election.
</P>
<P>
The firmer housing market picture was also shown by figures
offered by the British Bankers Association Tuesday, which said
that Britain's banks made gross home loans of 2.15 billion pounds
(3.5 billion US dollars) in February, three percent up on
January's figures.
</P>
<P>
However, the increases were much stronger at the same time a
year ago with both volume and value rising 32 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
