<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Manufacturing Growth Rate Slows Down in March </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 2 (Xinhua) -- The rate of growth in the
manufacturing sector of Britain's economy slowed in March to its
lowest level since last Summer, although it grew for the tenth
month in a row, as companies laid workers off to keep costs under
control.
</P>
<P>
The latest monthly purchasing managers' survey showed today
that the Purchasing Managers' Index, which takes account of a
range of indicators in determining the overall health of
manufacturing industry, fell from 53.4 to 52.9 in March, although
it was above the 50 points level that indicates the sector is
growing.
</P>
<P>
The Chartered Institute of Purchasing and Supply, which
prepares the figures, said the overall decline in the index was
mainly caused by the first fall in manufacturing employment for
almost a year.
</P>
<P>
For the first time, since May 1996, more managers reported a
lower level of employment than a higher level, and the employment
index dipped to 49.4, a fall of 1.5.
</P>
<P>
The survey found that the strong pound is also holding back
growth, with exports running at levels below those seen in the
last quater of 1996, although a pick-up in European markets led
to a slight improvement in the month's export output figures.
</P>
<P>
The strong pound also meant prices paid for raw materials and
components fell for the 17th months in a row in March.
</P>
<P>
However, analysts said that the figures were unlikely to change
the current view that official interest rates would rise by 0.25
percent soon after the general election on May 1. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
