<HEADLINE> 4 Million Tourists Visit Egypt in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Four million tourists visited Egypt
in 1996, a 24.3 percent rise over the previous year, the Egyptian
MENA news agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
A security report by the Egyptian Interior Ministry said that
Egypt received 2 million tourists in first half of 1996, nearly
half a million more than the same 1995 period.
</P>
<P>
It praised the efforts exerted by the tourism and antiquities
police department in guaranteeing the safety and security of
tourists visiting the country.
</P>
<P>
Egypt witnessed some militant attacks last year, triggering
fears that tourism, the country's second largest foreign currency
earner, might be hurt.
</P>
<P>
Last April, 18 Greek tourists were killed at the Europa Hotel
in Cairo suburb.
</P>
<P>
Despite the actions, the tourism revenues reached 3 billion
U.S. dollars in 1996, 710 million dollars more than that of 1995.
</P>
</TEXT>
