<DOCNO> XIE19970403.0035 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania Fully Commited to Support Development of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
(By Pei Shanqin)
</P>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian Prime Minister Frederick
Sumaye affirmed here today Tanzania's full commitment, support and
co-operation in ensuring that the Permanent Tripartite Commission of
the East African Co-operation (EAC) fulfils its mandate.
</P>
<P>
The Secretariat of the Commission of the EAC was officially
launched by the presidents of Kenya, Tanzania and Uganda in Arusha,
northern Tanzania, in March last year.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a state banquet for his Ugandan counterpart, Kintu
Musoke, Sumaye said that the work of the commission must be
supported fully.
</P>
<P>
"It is encouraging to note that the commission has put its main
focus on areas which are focal points to our economic growth," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Musoke, who is leading a delegation of two cabinet ministers,
high-ranking governemnt officials and businessmen, arrived here
this morning for a five-day official visit to Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
The Tanzanian prime minister said that there were many
obstacles to be overcome as the region embarked the consolidation
of gains through co-operation, but he expressed optimism that the
three east African countries will achieve success.
</P>
<P>
"In the final analysis the main objective of our co-operation is
to promote economic growth in order to improve the standard of
living of our people and eradicate poverty," he said.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister pointed out that in the spirit of south-south
co-operation the east African people stood at a better position to
making maximum use of the material, financial and human resources
which are available in the region.
</P>
<P>
Sumaye also commended the vision of promoting the role of the
private sector as an engine of economic growth in the sub-region.
</P>
<P>
He said the role of the private sector in bringing about change was
well recognised and appreciated in all the three countries, and expresed
the hope that the sector will take up the challenge.
</P>
<P>
"Private entrepreneurs must take up the challenge to utilise fully
the current enabling policy environment to work towards the
realization of more interaction and understanding in order to increase
the volume of investments and trade across our borders," he said.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister also said that bilateral co-operation
arrangements were foundation stones in economic intergration.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated Tanzania's stand in continuing to co-operate with
Uganda in the development of the trasport corridor to Uganda which he
said was an direct route for goods to and from the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
"We will continue to avail port and transport facilities for
Ugandan transit cargo," he said. "The challenge is to the Ugandan
institutions to make full use of the facilities."
</P>
<P>
Sumaye, however, stressed the need to improve efficiency and
security at the harbour and transport facilities, saying that both
were being dealt with effectively.  enditem

