<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-02 18:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Doctors Adviced Not to Stage Strike in Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Cypriot health authorites today
advised doctors in state-run hospitals not to stage strike and
described the measures as "the worst choice."
</P>
<P>
Doctors at state hospitals has announced that they will stage a
48-hour strike Thursday and Friday in support of their demand
for a pay rise and structural changes in hospitals.
</P>
<P>
The civil servants trade union PASIDY has given the green light
for the strike while stressing today that no lives will be put in
danger as a result of the strike.
</P>
<P>
Doctors have said that safety committees will operate on
the two days of the strike to deal with emergency cases.
</P>
<P>
"We decided to go on strike because, despite our attempts,
no meeting has taken place with officials to discuss the
problems government doctors are facing," PASIDY's General Secretary
Glafcos Hadjipetrou said today.
</P>
<P>
Health Minister Manolis Christofides said in a letter to
PASIDY that "the choice to take strike measures is, under the
circumstances, the worst choice."
</P>
<P>
He said that "if you insist on strike measures to achieve your
goals, we do not believe it would be possible for a
self-respective government to give in under the pressure of a
strike."
</P>
<P>
Doctors at state hospitals went on a 24-hour warning
strike on March 13. As a result, all hospitals in all
districts on the island, including rural clinics and out-patients
units were paralyzed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
