<HEADLINE> Mogadishu Warring Factions Hold Top-Level Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, April 2 (Xinhua) -- A top-level meeting between the
warring factions in the Somali capital went into a second
day today.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-two delegates, half appointed by north Mogadishu
faction leader Ali Mahdi Mohamed and half by south Mogadishu
faction leader Hussein Mohamed Aidid, were discussing ways of
resolving the long-standing political misunderstanding between
them.
</P>
<P>
A delegate said the main topics include how to achieve a
lasting political solution, the pacification of the capital and
the reopening of the Mogadishu airport and seaports.
</P>
<P>
In another development, a high-level traditional meeting
chaired by Imam Mohamud Iman Omar, the Imam of Hirab clan which
both Ali Mahdi and Hussein Aidid belong to, closed today.
</P>
<P>
The decisions made at the traditional meeting today include
the cessation of hostilities, the restoration of properties to
their rightful owners and the unconditional release of the
hostages held by the two sides.
</P>
<P>
The traditional meeting today appointed a standing committee
to manage to open all roads linking south and north Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
The political committees of the two sides applauded for the
decisions and promised full supports to their implementation.
</P>
<P>
Madame Khadija Ossoble Ali, from the Coalition Grass Roots of
Women Organization (COGWO) and one of the founders of the
traditional meeting, told Xinhua that four official meetings have
been held to end the killings and abductions in Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
The decisions resulted in the release of Elmi ahmed Yol, the
so-called Environment Minister of Hussein Mohamed Aidid's
self-styled government, who had been in captivity in south
Mogadishu for several weeks, and of Salad Mohamed Shardi, one of
Somalia's most popular singers from north Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
The release of the two men was welcomed by the two main
faction leaders. enditem

