<DOCNO> XIE19970403.0048 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania May Exempt Some Imported Goods From VAT </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 2 (Xinhua) -- A number of raw materials,
agricultural supplies and social services will be exempted from
the Value Added Tax (VAT) in Tanzania if a bill concerned is
endorsed by the parliament.
</P>
<P>
According to the official Daily News, the bill will go to a
parliamentary session in Dodoma, Central Tanzania, next Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Under the bill, items for exemption include food and livestock
supplies, pesticides, fertilizers and health supplies.
</P>
<P>
Others included educational and veterinary supplies while
transport, funeral, financial and insurance services will also
be exempted from VAT.
</P>
<P>
The supply of water, except bottled or canned or similarly
presented drinking water, will also be exempted from VAT.
</P>
<P>
The bill, if endorsed, is expected to be operational on July
1, 1998.
</P>
<P>
The VAT, to replace the current sales tax, will also entail
special reliefs on goods imported by diplomats or a diplomatic
mission accredited to Tanzania where the foreign countries
provides reciprocal treatment for Tanzanian counterparts.
</P>
<P>
The special reliefs also cover supplies or importations of
goods or services under a technical aid agreement as far as that
agreement provides for relief from Tanzania taxation.
</P>
<P>
If the bill is passed, it will also entail the amendment of
the Hotel Levy Act of 1972 whereby no hotel levy will be charged
on all VAT registered persons with being effective from July 1,
next year.
</P>
<P>
According to the bill, VAT shall be charged at the rate of
20 percent on the taxable value and its scope will include any
supply of goods or services determined to be taxable supplies.
</P>
<P>
Any people who fail to submit a return or pay taxes within
specified dates will have committed an offence and is liable for
a fine not exceeding 200,000 Tanzania Shillings (about 330 U.S.
Dollars), or for imprisonment of no less than two months.
enditem

