<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France to Return 3 Masterpieces Robbed by Nazis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 2 (Xinhua) -- France will return three masterpiece
paintings robbed by the Nazis during World War II and now kept in
a national gallery to its original owners or their heirs, said a
French Foreign Ministry spokesman today.
</P>
<P>
The three paintings are "Tete de Femme (Head of Woman)" painted
by Pablo Picasso in 1921, "Paysage (Country)" by Albert Gleizes in
1911, and "Deux Femme Nues (Two Nude Women)" by Tsugouharu Foujita
in 1929, said Foreign Ministry spokesman Yves Doutriaux.
</P>
<P>
A total of 2,000 artistic works recovered by France from
Germans after World War II remain unclaimed yet by their original
owners, most of whom are believed to have died in Nazi death
camps.
</P>
<P>
The people who claimed the three paintings, now kept in the
Centre Georges Pompidou art gallery in Paris, have required
anonymity, said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
In November 1996, French Foreign Minister Herve de Charette
returned to its owner a painting by naturalist painter
Leon-Augustin Lhermitte, which was taken back by France together
with 27 other paintings from the National Gallery of Berlin in
1994.
</P>
<P>
Since the end of World War II, altogether 100,000 artistic
works which were taken back from Germans by France have been
claimed by their original owners, most of them Jews, according to
the Foreign Ministry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970403.0050 </DOCNO>
