<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Liberia's New Electoral Commission Inaugurates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 2 (Xinhua) -- A new independent electoral
commission for Liberia's May 30 polls inaugurated today in
Monrovia, the Liberian capital, with veteran journalist Henry
Andrews as the chairman.
</P>
<P>
Gloria Scott, who represents former warlord Charles Taylor and
his National Patriotic Party of Liberia, became vice-chairman of
the commission, said a report reaching here today.
</P>
<P>
The commission should have been inducted about two weeks ago
but disagreement over the chairmanship had twice delayed the
constitution of it.
</P>
<P>
Worrying about whether Liberia's elections can be held on May
30 as scheduled, the chairman of the Economic Community of West
African States (ECOWAS), Nigeria's Head of State General Sani
Abacha, has asked Liberia to induct the commission today.
</P>
<P>
Abacha, a broker of Liberia's peace, has mandated Nigerian
Foreign Affairs Minister Tom Ikimi to go to Liberia to constitute
an independent electoral commission acceptable to both the
Liberian people and the former warring factions.
</P>
<P>
Ikimi, who arrived in Monrovia on Tuesday, said at today's
inauguration ceremony that the induction of the commission is an
important step towards the national polls.
</P>
<P>
He called on Liberia's ruling Council of State, political
parties and all Liberians to work together to ensure the
elections to be held as scheduled.
</P>
<P>
According to an agreement reached by ECOWAS heads of state in
Abuja, Nigeria, last year, the electoral commission will comprise
10 members, including three delegates respectively from the
United Nations, the Organization of African Unity and ECOWAS.
</P>
<P>
A retired Nigeria diplomat has been appointed as the
representative of ECOWAS and left for Liberia.
</P>
<P>
The other seven members will separately come from three former
major warring factions, youth's organization, women's group, trade
unions and the coalition of political parties.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970403.0053 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> African Medical Experts Combat Malaria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YAOUNDE, April 2 (Xinhua) -- A workshop is being held here to
define strategies for curbing acute malaria, the number one
killer disease in Africa.
</P>
<P>
Medical experts from 13 African countries are attending the
workshop, which started Tuesday and was sponsored by the World
Health Organization (WHO).
</P>
<P>
During the two-week workshop, medical experts will share
experiences and learn methods of eradicating acute malaria so as
to improve their knowledge and practices in health personnel
training and in tackling severe malaria cases.
</P>
<P>
They are expected to map out plans for health personnel in
their countries.
</P>
<P>
Malaria is one of the most important health concerns in more
than 90 countries in the world with an incidence of 300 to 500
million cases each year, almost 90 percent of the cases in
Sub-Sahara Africa.
</P>
<P>
Some one million Camerounians suffer from malaria each year.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Public Health Minister Titus Edzoa said that 30
percent of the deaths in the country's hospitals are
malaria-related.
</P>
<P>
He added that most of the deaths are children under age
five.
</P>
<P>
A doctor from the Comoros said malaria is the first
cause of infant mortality and kills 18 to 20 percent of all
patients in his country although a national program was launched
15 years ago for curbing malaria in that country.
</P>
<P>
An expert from Chad said malaria is virtually unheard of in
the northern part of Chad but remains the number one killer
disease in the south of the country. enditem

=04022049

=04022056
NNNN
04:54 04:54 g # PAB
</P>
