<HEADLINE> France Hails Presence of Greek Troops in Albania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 2 (Xinhua) -- French Defense Minister Charles
Millon today hailed the plan by Greece to send 700 soldiers to
Albania to join the international protection force in the Balkan
state.
</P>
<P>
During a meeting with his Greek counterpart, Akis
Tsohatzopoulos, Millon said that he is happy that French and Greek
soldiers can be deployed side by side in Albania to ensure the
arrival of humanitarian aid to Albanian people.
</P>
<P>
France will send 1,000 soldiers to Albania to guard the
unloading of international humanitarian goods at the port of
Durres and their transport to the capital Tirana.
</P>
<P>
The multinational protection force, proposed by the
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe and approved
by the United Nations Security Council last week, will be headed
by Italy and also joined by Spain and Turkey. They will arrive in
Albania by April 10.
</P>
<P>
Millon and Tsohatzopoulos also discussed bilateral relations
between France and Greece, security in the Mediterranean region,
and the construction of the West European Union and the North
Atlantic Alliance.
</P>
<P>
"I can tell a great convergence of views (between France and
Greece). We hope that the initiatives taken in the framework of
the United Nations will lead to the positive solutions (of the
Albanian crisis) and allow the reinforcement of security and the
guarantee of peace in this region of Europe," said Millon.
</P>
<P>
He also said that he and Tsohatzopoulos agreed that NATO should
reach an agreement with Russia and Ukraine over NATO expansion,
and that Romania should be admitted by NATO in the first wave of
its expansion. 
</P>
