<HEADLINE> British Opposition Party Launches Manifesto </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 3 (Xinhua) -- British opposition Labor Party
launched its manifesto today, promising not to raise income tax
rates, guarantee low inflation, create jobs and put education the
number one priority if it wins the May 1 election.
</P>
<P>
Announcing the 10-point manifesto, Labor leader Tony Blair
vowed to undertake state health and welfare reform.
</P>
<P>
He would impose heavy tax on windfall profits of water, gas,
electricity and other companies, which were privatized by the
Conservatives, to create jobs for 250,000 people in the dole
queues.
</P>
<P>
Blair said his "contract with people" also included a
wide-range reform in education and a reinforcement of Britain's
role in Europe.
</P>
<P>
He said the manifesto was not a radical program, but "in tune
with the times and instincts of today's Britain."
</P>
<P>
The ruling Conservatives published their manifesto on
Wednesday, promising income tax cuts, public service reform and
fighting crimes.
</P>
<P>
Labor led Prime Minister John Major's Conservatives by 27
points in a latest opinion poll.
</P>
<P>
Blair, 43, would be Britain's youngest prime minister of this
century if he beats Major in the election. 
