<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Should Accelerate Medical Guarantee System Reforms: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 3 (Xinhua) -- China should accelerate its
reforms of the medical guarantee system covering urban workers and
staffs of government institutions, a government official said
today.
</P>
<P>
The present medical guarantee system, established in early 1950s,
are no longer suitable to the demands of a socialist market
economy in China, Song Xiaowu, director of the Distribution and
Social Security Department of the State Commission for Economic
Restructuring, said here at an on-going international seminar on
social guarantee funds management.
</P>
<P>
The old system, under which all medical expenses are borne by
the government, institutions, and enterprises, lacks an effective
mechanism to impose restrictions on both the hospitals and
patients, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Doctors in some hospitals often over-prescribed medicine or
wrote out the so-called human relationship prescription, and the
employee's family members and relatives got the medicine easily
because of his entitlement to public health services, resulting in
huge losses," Song explained.
</P>
<P>
The practice of all expenses covered by the state, government
institutions, or enterprises lacks a rational mechanism to raise
social medical funds and encourage the individuals to accumulate
funds, he said.
</P>
<P>
Covering only the government departments, institutions, state
firms, and a part of the collective enterprises, the old system can
not meet the demand of a common development of various economic
sectors and hampers the rational flow of the labor forces among
enterprises of different ownership, he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
Figures provided by the Ministry of Finance show that the
medical expenditures of Chinese workers nationwide totaled 2.7
billion yuan in 1978 and surged to 55.8 billion yuan in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Official data also show that the per person-time medical
expenses grew an average 30 percent between 1991 and 1995 in
hospitals at the provincial, prefectural, and county levels and
those directly under the Ministry of Public Health, far exceeding
the increase rate of the gross domestic product during the same
period.
</P>
<P>
In an official survey of 1,000 workers last year, 47 percent of
the respondents, or the largest proportion, said that they were
most concerned about the reform in the medical guarantee system,
</P>
<P>
"This manifests the necessity and urgency to accelerate the
reform of the medical guarantee system," Song said.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese Government has taken a positive and reliable step
toward medical guarantee system reform for it is a very
complicated work, he noted.
</P>
<P>
In early 1994, the cities of Zhenjiang and Jiujiang, in
eastern Jiangsu and Jiangxi provinces, were selected to pilot a
medical guarantee system reform program, which was expanded to
over 50 cities in early 1996.
</P>
<P>
Considerable progress has been made in the experimental areas,
Song said.
</P>
<P>
He added that the objectives of China's medical guarantee
system reform are to set up a social medicare security system that
combines overall social planning funds with contributions from
personal savings and to make the system cover all laborers in
cities and towns.
</P>
<P>
The three-day seminar, co-sponsored by the Ministry of Finance
and Lincoln National Corporation of the United States, was
launched Wednesday.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970403.0059 </DOCNO>
