<HEADLINE> Nujoma Willing to Continue Presidential Term </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Namibian President Sam
Nujoma has told national parliament that he would accept a third
term in office if asked to do so, reports reaching here today
said.
</P>
<P>
"I am still young... and if the people of Namibia want me to
continue making a contribution, I will do so," Nujoma, 67, told a
parliamentary joint sitting on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Under the Namibian constitution, a state president may only
hold office for two five-year terms.
</P>
<P>
Nujoma told BBC reporters last year that he would step down
when his second five-year expired in 1999. However, in a later
interview he told Zimbabwe state TV that he would stay on if
asked to do so by the people and the ruling South West Africa
People's Organization (SWAPO).
</P>
<P>
More recently, he told the state-run newspaper New Era that he
would be ready to resign in 1999, the Namibian newspaper
reported.
</P>
<P>
At its congress last month, the SWAPO Elders Council voted to
ask Nujoma to stand for a third term.
</P>
<P>
South African Press Association quoted political observers as
saying that the subject would be likely to top the agenda at a
SWAPO congress scheduled for later this year. 
</P>
