<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian Foreign Minister Ali
Alatas today rapped a number of foreign media for spreading rumors
about President Soeharto's health in the past few days.
</P>
<P>
"Their reports about the president's health have been negative.
Some were also speculative," he said after meeting with Soeharto
at the Bina Graha presidential office.
</P>
<P>
In the last several days, certain foreign media have been
sending out reports that the president was having some problems
with his health.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, one of them even reported that Soeharto suffered
from a "mild stroke" which then affected the activities of the
Jakarta Stock Exchange as well as the bourses in the neighboring
countries.
</P>
<P>
Alatas said the foreign press should concentrate on following
President Soeharto's activities instead of spreading such rumors.
</P>
<P>
During his meeting with Soeharto, Alatas reported his planned
visit to India for the ministerial meeting of the Non-Aligned
Movement (NAM) scheduled to take place from April 7 to 8.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the NAM meeting, Alatas will also pay a working visit
to India.
</P>
<P>
On the sidelines of the NAM meeting, Alatas will hold talks
with foreign ministers of the countries which once chaired the NAM
and also with his counterparts from ASEAN.
</P>
<P>
All the seven members of the Association of Southeast Asian
Nations (ASEAN) -- Brunei, Indonesia, Malaysia, the Philippines,
Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam -- are also members of the NAM.
</P>
<P>
"The meeting with my ASEAN colleagues will take place on April
7. However, there will be no specific agenda for the occasion," he
said.
</P>
<P>
There are about four major topics to be discussed. "They are
about how to enhance the role of the NAM in the international
politics, how to eradicate poverty, how to carry out better
coordination to reform the U.N. and how to handle the issues of
nuclear disarmament," Alatas said. 
</P>
