<HEADLINE> Textbooks Teach Farmers To Live A Healthy Life (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 3 (Xinhua) -- "Which kinds of infectious
diseases can humans get from sheep and pigs?" "Why should people
take iodized salt?" "How can hepatitis be prevented?"
</P>
<P>
Such questions are not just discussed by well-schooled
physicians: poorly-educated Chinese farmers also want answers, and
will get them thanks to a new series of books on health-related
questions that are common in China's vast rural areas, where three
fourths of the country's 1.2 billion population live.
</P>
<P>
The first 10,000 three-volume sets, titled "Textbooks of Health
Education for 900-Million Chinese Farmers," will be distributed
free of charge to rural households in seven provinces, as well as
the municipalities of Beijing and Tianjin.
</P>
<P>
Hunan Science &AMP; Technology Publishing House, the publisher,
announced the book donation program in Beijing today, hoping the
texts will play a successful role in China's nationwide campaign
to spread health knowledge among rural residents.
</P>
<P>
"I believed these will be very helpful textbooks for both
doctors in the countryside and farmers," said Minister of Health
Chen Minzhang, who is leading the campaign, launched in 1994.
</P>
<P>
The books are written plainly with easy-to-understand
expressions, and some include illustrations.
</P>
<P>
The volumes include more than 1,200 questions and answers
covering every aspect of rural residents' health, such as basic
knowledge about diseases commonly existing in rural areas,
treatments, healthy birth, good hygiene, and sexual education.
</P>
<P>
"Considering the generally low education level of farmers, we
have to make sure that they can understand the books," said one of
the editors.
</P>
<P>
To do so, the authors went to villages to talk with farmers
until they were satisfied the books were understandable, the
editor said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970403.0064 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Textbooks Published To Teach Farmers Live A Healthy Life (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"In addition to video and cassette tapes, the textbooks will
become a helpful tool for teaching farmers health know-how,
because they are easy to buy and can be referred to often," said
an official involved in the educational campaign.
</P>
<P>
China's health authorities, in concert with agricultural, radio
and television departments, have produced more than 100 video and
radio programs of health education in the past three years. Most
of them have been broadcast in rural areas by national and local
radio and TV stations.
</P>
<P>
However, health officials admitted that it is still a hard work
to further improve health conditions of Chinese farmers, despite
big strides which have been made in the past four decades.
</P>
<P>
Due to low education level, poor health awareness, and
unhealthy lifestyles, many Chinese farmers are vulnerable to
illnesses, including iodine deficiency, snail fever, hepatitis and
tuberculosis, they said.
</P>
<P>
"The worse thing is that treatment for the illnesses may cost
farmers too much and they will be poorer than before," an official
said.
</P>
<P>
A survey showed that among poor farmers, 60 to 70 percent were
reduced to poverty by huge medical expenses.
</P>
<P>
Both health officials and medical experts believe the poor
health condition of the rural population will be the biggest
challenge facing China's goal of "health for everyone" by the year
2000.
</P>
<P>
"We will make greater efforts to improve farmers' health
conditions since the central government has urged us to place
utmost importance on this job in the next 15 years," said Health
Minister Chen Minzhang.
</P>
<P>
"But maybe the most important thing is that farmers should
learn how to protect themselves from diseases," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
