<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK's Freedom of the Press Fully Guaranteed After Its Return (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Freedom of the press in Hong Kong
will be fully guaranteed and protected by law in accordance with
the provisions of the Basic Law of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region after it returns to the motherland, China's
top information officer said today.
</P>
<P>
Zeng Jianhui, director of the Information Office of the State
Council, made the remark here today while speaking at a forum to
mark the seventh anniversary on April 4 of the promulgation of the
Basic Law.
</P>
<P>
The media in Hong Kong and throughout the world are greatly
concerned about the future of Hong Kong's freedom of the press, he
said.
</P>
<P>
In the Sino-British Joint Declaration on the Question of Hong
Kong, the Chinese government promised to guarantee Hong Kong
residents' freedom of speech and publication, he said.
</P>
<P>
During the drafting of the Basic Law, Zeng said, ensuring Hong
Kong residents' freedom of the press was specially included at the
request of the press circles in the region. This clearly shows
that the Basic Law specially guarantees freedom of the press, he
pointed out.
</P>
<P>
According to the provisions of the Basic Law, after Hong Kong
returns to the motherland on July 1, freedom of the press in Hong
Kong will be guaranteed and fully protected by law.
</P>
<P>
Zeng stressed that the information departments and institutions
in the Chinese inland areas and in Hong Kong will not be
subordinated to each other or interfere in each other's affairs.
</P>
<P>
The management method of the inland media shall not be used in
Hong Kong, and Hong Kong will act in accordance with its original
operation mechanism and rules of operation, he said.
</P>
<P>
Neither can Hong Kong's own way of managing the media be
adopted by the Chinese inland areas, he said, commenting that
"well water does not flow into river water, and vice versa."
</P>
<P>
The inland press and information departments will act in
accordance with the state laws for the inland areas, while Hong
Kong institutions with the Basic Law, he added. The inland
journalists should observe the Basic Law and other Hong Kong laws
while covering news in Hong Kong, while the Hong Kong journalists
also should abide by the inland laws when they cover news in the
inland areas, he stressed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970403.0067 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK's Freedom of the Press Fully Guaranteed After Its Return (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Of course, Zeng noted, any freedom is relative and limited;
there is no absolute freedom or freedom without limits in the
world.
</P>
<P>
"On the one hand we are talking about freedom of the press and
on the other hand we are stressing journalists' professional
ethics. News writing should be true and impartial," he said.
</P>
<P>
Zeng went on to say that no society will ever allow the media
to cheat the the public or misdirect public opinion by using
fabricated information, without considering its social
responsibility or the damage that can be caused to people's
reputations by vilification.
</P>
<P>
Criticizing such actions will not hinder freedom of the press,
but rather protect it, he said.
</P>
<P>
Zeng said in the world community, "we often hear such strange
stories as 'Hong Kong people are deprived of their democracy and
freedom', and 'Hong Kong's human rights are not guaranteed', which
are groundless charges against the Chinese government."
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong reversion bill adopted by the U.S. House of
Representatives in mid-March questioned, without good grounds,
whether the Chinese government will abide by the Sino-British
Joint Declaration after July 1, and made unwarranted charges
against the necessary measures China had taken to ensure Hong
Kong's smooth transition, he said.
</P>
<P>
Noting that a few Hong Kong people are "flapping their jaws" in
other parts of the world in an attempt to weaken Hong Kong and
discredit the Basic Law and Hong Kong, he said that these
discordant voices will not prevail over that of justice.
</P>
<P>
Zeng said Hong Kong's smooth transition is in keeping with the
will of the people and its prosperity and stability conforms to
people's expectations. He stressed that any attempt to create
disturbances, misguide world opinion and sabotage Hong Kong's
return will never be successful. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970403.0068 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Visitor Arrivals in Thailand Hit 7.2 Million </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Visitor arrivals in Thailand
totaled 7.19 million in 1996, up 3.46 percent from 1995, according
to figures released by the Tourism Authority of Thailand (TAT)
today.
</P>
<P>
The figure was in line with the overall target of 7.2 million
visitors forecast by the TAT for 1996.
</P>
<P>
The East Asian market, including member countries of the
Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN), continued to
generate the majority of visitors to Thailand, with a total of 4.5
million arrivals last year.
</P>
<P>
The only country generating more than one million visitors to
Thailand a year is Malaysia, with 1.056 million last year --
mostly border-crossers in South Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia was followed by japan, with 934,000 visitors, up 14.66
percent from 1995.
</P>
<P>
South Korea came third, with 489,000 arrivals.
</P>
<P>
For Thailand, China was the fastest growing Asian market in the
year, up about 22 percent, to reach 457,000, ranking fourth.
</P>
</TEXT>
