<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Global Telemedicine Conference to Mark HK's Handover </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 3 (Xinhua) -- A global telemedicine conference
has been scheduled to herald the historic handover of Hong Kong at
the midnight on June 30 this year.
</P>
<P>
Doctors and medical students at the Chinese University of Hong
Kong will be globe-trotting with the sun in the Global
Telemedicine Conference, a 24-hour live audiovisual link-up around
the world which starts at Prince of Wales Hospital at 4:00 PM on
June 30.
</P>
<P>
The organizers have adopted "Moving With the Sun" as its theme.
</P>
<P>
It will be the first telemedicine conference to make a full
sweep of the globe, according to Professor Mgnus Hjelm, chairman
of the university's Department of Chemical Pathology.
</P>
<P>
"The timing of the conference will better promote telemedicine
in Hong Kong as well as share the historic moment of the handover
with medical communities overseas. We received very enthusiastic
response from around the world to the idea of combining the two
events," he was quoted by local newspaper South China Morning Post
today as saying.
</P>
<P>
About 15 medical institutions in Europe, North America, South
America, Australia and Asia, including three in the Chinese
mainland, are expected to take part.
</P>
<P>
The conference will start and finish with communications with
the People's Liberation Army General Hospital in Beijing, which
will have a link with Hong Kong throughout the event.
</P>
<P>
Prince of Wales Hospital will introduce telemedicine in Hong
Kong and beam live broadcasts from Victoria Harbor, the Peak and
the Chinese University's campus in co-operation with commercial TV
stations.
</P>
<P>
Each of the international sites will be hooked up for about 60
to 90 minutes and changing links will be kept as the sun rises on
individual sites.
</P>
<P>
Contents of the conference include latest research and
development in telemedicine, interviews with local health
officials, showing physicians making rounds in hospitals and
comments from patients who have experienced clinical services
through telemedicine conference.
</P>
<P>
The use of telemedicine technology for education and providing
distance medical care and consultation at the Hong Kong university
has become more systematic since it held its first international
conference in November last year, the newspaper said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
