<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Motorola's Tianjin Plant takes
several firsts among the foreign-funded enterprises in the port
city in north China, according to Zhang Lichang, mayor of Tianjin.
</P>
<P>
"The plant is the No. 1 in terms of growth rate, economic
results, and production scale," he told the visiting Robert
Galvin, chairman of board of Motorola Corp.
</P>
<P>
Zhang said as one of China's major coastal opening-up cities,
Tianjin will continue its support for Motorola and welcomes all
other large corporations in the world to establish cooperation
with city.
</P>
<P>
Since Motorola's wholly-funded Tianjin Plant began operation in
1992, its volume of business has leapt from 50 million US dollars
to two billion dollars last year. The profits last year hit 350
million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the mobile phone production increased from 27,000
units four years ago to 2.1 million units, taking 40 percent of
the market share in China last year.
</P>
<P>
The company ranked second among China's top 500 foreign-funded
enterprises last year. Its investment in China has hit 1.2 billion
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Galvin paid a visit to China to mark the tenth anniversary of
Motorola in China.
</P>
<P>
Tianjin Wednesday granted Galvin an honorary citizenship.
</P>
