<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-03 12:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Drops Request for Hamas Chief Extradition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 3 (Xinhua) -- The Israeli government issued a
statement today announcing what it called a suspension in "its
request to extradite Hamas leader Mussa Abu Marzook to Israel."
</P>
<P>
According to the statement faxed to Xinhua by the Prime
Minister's Office, the Israeli government "has informed the
United States that at this stage it wishes to suspend its
request."
</P>
<P>
"The decision was made by the Prime Minister and other
ministers dealing with the issue after consultations with the
relevant legal and security authorities," said the document,
adding that the decision was made on the basis of considerations
"relating to security and the prevention of terrorism."
</P>
<P>
Abu Marzook, a 46-year-old Hamas political leader, was
arrested by the U.S. police in New York 20 months ago on
charges that he had connections with Hamas suicide bombing
attacks in Israel.
</P>
<P>
Israel originally wanted the U.S. authorities concerned to
extradite Abu Marzook to the Jewish state for trial. In January,
Abu Marzook gave up his fight against extradition and said he
wanted to go to Israel to face the alleged charges.
</P>
<P>
As there is no sound evidence to support the charges, the case
has turned into a political hot potato both for the U.S. and
Israel. The latter fears that should Abu Marzook be brought to the
country, it would be tantamount to inviting Hamas to launch a new
wave of retaliatory attacks in Israel.
</P>
<P>
Abu Marzook's announcement set in motion a 60-day clock for
extradiltion. His lawyer Michael Kennedy demanded this week that
his client be released from the federal jail in New York  because
60 days had passed.
</P>
<P>
However, U.S. Federal Prosecutor Baruch Weiss argued that the
60-day mark is Sunday. He also said ironically that the
U.S. could continue to hold Abu Marzook because there is a
separate immigration case pending against him. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
