<HEADLINE> Palestinian Official Denies Reports of Possible </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 3 (Xinhua) -- A senior Palestinian official
denied today reports that Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat
planned to meet with Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu
in Washington this week.
</P>
<P>
Nabil Abu Rudeineh, Secretary-General of the Palestinian
National Authority (PNA), told Palestinian Radio that Arafat had
no plan to travel to Washington in the coming days.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks while commenting on the media reports that
U.S. President Bill Clinton would possibly host a three-way summit
to solve the current crisis over the Israeli-Palestinian track of
the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Arafat's spokesman Marwan Kanafani said Wednesday that the
U.S. government was making efforts to arrange an Arafat-Netanyahu
summit when the latter travels to Washington this weekend. He said
the U.S. asked both Israel and the PNA to send representatives to
the U.S. capital to discuss the possibility of holding such a
summit.
</P>
<P>
Rudeineh confirmed that U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright made a telephone call to Arafat Wednesday to discuss the
current situation. he said Albright expressed her willingness to
visit the Middle East soon in a bid to defuse the tension and
restart the stalled peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Both the U.S. State Department and Israeli Prime Minister's
Office have denied the possibility of holding an Arafat-Netanyahu
meeting this week.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Israel said Netanyahu would hold a summit with
Jordanian King Hussein in Washington Sunday, which the the
monarch is currently visiting while undergoing a medical surgery.
</P>
<P>
Regarding reports that Clinton would press Netanyahu to freeze
the controversial Har Homa settlement construction for six months
during their meeting next Monday, Netanyahu's spokesman Shai
Bazak said the Israeli prime minister would make clear to the
U.S. that his country retained the right to build settlements
either in East Jerusalem or elsewhere on the Palestinian
territories.
</P>
<P>
Bazak said the purpose of Netanyahu's Washington visit was to
underscore Israel's demand on the PNA to launch a long-term
crackdown on extremism as the condition to resume the peace
talks. 
</P>
