<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Saudi Players not Banned for Alleged Doping </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Three Saudi Arabia nationals
who tested positive for doping last year will not be punished due
to possible discrepancies in doping procedure, the Asian soccer
body AFC said here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
AFC Secretary-general Peter Velappan said the world soccer body
FIFA has investigated the case which happened during December's
Asia Cup tournament and ruled that it was not possible to take any
disciplinary action against the players.
</P>
<P>
He said there were some discrepancies in the execution of the
doping control and the findings were invalid.
</P>
<P>
He added that the Saudi Arabia Football Association
categorially outruled the possibility of the trio taking any drugs
and later asked AFC to look into the matter.
</P>
<P>
Responding to AFC's request to investigate, he said, FIFA
formed a three-member independent panel, which reported there were
discrepancies in the execution of the doping control there.
</P>
<P>
Velappan declined to give the names of the three players, but
adding that AFC will improve the doping control procedure in
future competitions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
