<HEADLINE> Chinese Premier Meets Japanese Kansai Business Delegation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Premier Li Peng met today
with a Japanese Kansai business delegation co-headed by Tetsuro
Kawakami, chairman of the Kansai Economic Federation, and Masafumi
Onishi, chairman of the Osaka Chamber of Commerce and Industry.
</P>
<P>
Li Peng extended welcome to the delegation's China trip and
expressed his appreciation to Kansai business circles for their
efforts in advancing the Sino-Japanese economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
This year marks the 25th anniversary of the normalization of
relations between China and Japan, Li said. In Japan, he noted,
the force standing for Sino-Japanese friendship from generation to
generation so as to effect a healthy and stable development of the
bilateral relations constitutes the main current. So long as both
sides abide by the principles provided in the Sino-Japanese Joint
Statement and the Sino-Japanese Treaty of Peace and Friendship,
the relations between the two countries would be continuously
improved and developed, Li Peng added.
</P>
<P>
The economic ties and trade between the two countries have been
developing rapidly in recent years, with two-way trade volume so
far exceeding 60 billion U.S. dollars, Li Peng said, hoping that
the good development trend would continue.
</P>
<P>
Li Peng welcomed the delegation to visit and establish economic
links with Chongqing, China's fourth municipality directly under
the Central Government. Japanese businesspeople are welcome to
invest more in China's central and western areas and conduct
economic cooperation there, he said.
</P>
<P>
Li Peng thanked the delegation for its condolences at the
passing away of Deng Xiaoping. The Chinese government would carry
on Deng Xiaoping's will and advance the reform, opening up, and
modernization drive.
</P>
<P>
Kawakami said the Kansai business circles established economic
links with China in early 1970s and made contributions to the
development of the Japan-China economic cooperation. Kansai
businesspeople wish to continue their efforts in this regard,
Kawakami said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
