<DOCNO> XIE19970403.0095 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S.Korea's Foreign Debt Surpasses 100 Billion Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, April 3 (Xinhua) -- South Korea's foreign debts totaled
104.5 billion U.S. dollars at the end of 1996, 33.3 percent more
than that of the previous year, the Bank of Korea (BOK) said today.
</P>
<P>
The 1996 figure, exceeding 100 billion dollars for the first
time, represents 21.8 percent of the gross national product (GNP)
in the same year.
</P>
<P>
Given the nation's overseas assets of 69.8 billion dollars at
the end of last year, the central bank said, net foreign debts
reached 34.7 billion dollars, two times more than the 17.1 billion
dollars at the end of 1995.
</P>
<P>
The structure of foreign debts also deteriorated as the ratio
of less-than-one-year debts to total debts went from 43.7 percent
in 1993 up to 53.4 percent in 1994, 57.8 percent in 1995 and 58.2
percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Since the nation's current account balance shifted from surplus
to deficit in 1990, the situation of the foreign debts has
aggravated rapidly, a BOK spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
South Korea suffered a record current account deficit of 23.7
billion dollars last year and a total 5.6 billion dollars deficit
in the first two months this year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the central bank said South Korea's foreign exchange
reserves plunged to 29.2 billion dollars a month ago. The figure
was the smallest since June 1995, when foreign exchange reserves
were only 28.4 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
However, a BOK official downplayed any fear of a financial
crisis, noting that "comparing the level of foreign debts with the
nation's basic economic conditions, there is no possibility that a
foreign exchange crisis will take place." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
