<HEADLINE> China's Bohai Gulf Expecting 10 million Tons of Oil Annually </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, April 3 (Xinhua) -- The Bohai Oilfield, near the
largest port city in north China, has decided on a new
development strategy that may help it boost annual production
capacity to 10 million tons by the year 2005.
</P>
<P>
Experts have explained the strategy as scientific planning and
overall development over four different oil exploration centers
within the oilfield.
</P>
<P>
The four are: the Liaobei oil exploration center, consisting of
the Jinzhou 20-2 and Jinzhou 9-3 lesser fields; the Liaozhong
center, based on Suizhong 36-1; the Shijiuzhai center, based on
Qinhuangdao 32-6; and a development center that combines the Boxi
and Bozhong oilfields.
</P>
<P>
Exploration since 1985 has proven that the Bohai Gulf abounds
in oil and gas, and oil reserves in the Bohai Oilfield are said to
be 800 million tons.
</P>
<P>
Bohai will use different oil exploration and development
methods according to conditions in the four centers to meet its
goals.
</P>
<P>
Bohai Oil Company was originally set up in Tanggu, in Tianjin,
in October of 1966, and now has 10 billion yuan in fixed assets
and 10,000 employees.
</P>
<P>
The oilfield the company now commands has an area of 60,000 sq
km and can produce two million tons of oil annually. 
</P>
</TEXT>
