<HEADLINE> Human Rights Issue Needs Dialogue: FM Spokesman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 3 (Xinhua) -- China is ready to dialogue and
cooperate with other countries to settle the issue of human rights
on the basis of mutual respect and equality, Chinese Foreign
Ministry Spokesman Shen Guofang said at a routine press conference
here today.
</P>
<P>
Shen said that at the U.N. Human Rights Conference in Geneva, a
motion, raised by the U.S. and some western countries to criticize
China's human rights conditions, is an interference in China's
internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
There are differences between China and some other countries on
the issue of human rights, he said, adding that these can be
resolved through dialogue.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that some countries should not criticize China
at the Geneva Human Rights Conference publicly and utterly
groundlessly.
</P>
<P>
He said that dialogue and confrontation are exclusive to each
other. Dialogue can reduce and even remove differences, while
confrontation can only make things more complicated.
</P>
<P>
The dialogue between China and other countries will begin if
those parties give up confrontation in the Geneva conference, he
said.
</P>
<P>
He said China wants to resolve the issue through dialogue and
hopes that the relevant countries can take practical measures to
eliminate confrontation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
