<DOCNO> XIE19970403.0102 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Production Drop Causes Fuel Scarcity in Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 3 (Xinhua) -- The drastic drop in the production
of Nigerian refineries has led to fuel scarcity in parts of
Nigeria, particularly Lagos and its environs, over the past two
weeks.
</P>
<P>
It is nothing to be surprised these days at the sight of an
oil-strained paperboard with the words "Sorry, No Fuel" at the
entrance of many Lagos filling stations.
</P>
<P>
Drivers in the Nigerian commercial center have also got used
to the long queues in the few filling stations that have
on-and-off fuel supply, only with fears that they can hardly find
queues to join.
</P>
<P>
"I'm lucky to get a full tank yesterday after waiting at a
filling station for three hours," said a driver who works for a
Lagos-based Chinese company.
</P>
<P>
"It normally takes more time, and some of my colleagues had
the experience of queuing for a whole night," he said.
</P>
<P>
The short supply of fuel has activated the black market in
parts of Lagos, as it is easy to get fuel at a double price
around some filling stations that have fuel to sell.
</P>
<P>
Relatives and acquaintants of some filling stations staff are
collaborating in the deals.
</P>
<P>
With the arrival of petrol, the staff, while serving drivers
who are usually tired of long-time queuing as usual, also pump
petrol into various plastic containers and carry them to their
friends waiting outside the premise for sale right at the foot of
the wall.
</P>
<P>
Lagos filling stations depend on local petrol marketers that
get delivery from either nearby pumping stations or vessels with
imported product.
</P>
<P>
But until last Saturday, major oil marketers in Lagos only
received 6.4 million liters of the expected 26.5 million liters
of petrol from a vessel of the Nigerian National Petroleum
Corporation (NNPC).
</P>
<P>
It could only last till Tuesday, according to today's Daily
Times.
</P>
<P>
"The problem is far from being solved, as we were told to
expect fresh delivery tomorrow (Friday) which may never come,"
said oil marketing officials, quoted by the largest Nigerian
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
The current fuel scarcity, in fact, is resulted from the big
decline in the output of the country's refineries, which now can
meet only 43 percent of the national total demand.
</P>
<P>
According to sources at the Pipelines and Products Marketing
Company (PPMC), a NNPC subsidiary, supplies from the three
functioning refineries in the country have dropped to 7.74
million liters per day, compared to the national consumption
level of 18 million liters.
</P>
<P>
While production from the 150,000 barrels per day in the new
Port Harcourt Refinery has been halved, output from Kaduna
Refinery has equally dropped from three million to 1.7 million
liters.
</P>
<P>
Lack of funds to embark on maintenance work at the refineries
is responsible for the decline in output.
</P>
<P>
According to the Nigerian government's 1997 budget, 200
million U.S. dollars will be allocated for refinery maintenance
this year. The sum, though short of the 800 million dollars
required, is yet to be released, said NNPC officials.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the slash in crude oil allocation to domestic
refineries from 300,000 barrels per day to 250,000 barrels has
already created a drop in processing of petroleum products for
national consumption from 18 million liters to 14.5 million.
</P>
<P>
All this indicates that the current fuel shortage in the
country may last longer than expected. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970403.0103 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Unveil Four Refined Films </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 3 (Xinhua) -- China will soon release four
well-lensed mainstream films nationwide, to compete with Hollywood
imports, and revive the national film industry.
</P>
<P>
Official sources say that overseas movies have dominated
China's film market in recent years, while lack of funds have
hampered Chinese film studio production.
</P>
<P>
The four films to be shown are "Strategic Turning Point", "Red
River Valley", "Days without Hero", and the comedy "My Husband is
a Null".
</P>
<P>
"Strategic Turning Point" is about the life story of the past
Chinese leader Deng Xiaoping who led his army into the Dabieshan
Mountains with Liu Bocheng in 1946, and smoothed the way for the
overwhelming victory of the Chinese Communist Party over the
Kuomintang on the Chinese mainland in 1949.
</P>
<P>
The film "Red River Valley" is based on a true story about the
Chinese and Tibetan people who fought against British invaders in
1890.
</P>
<P>
The four movies are considered the best of the 110 Chinese
films produced last year, Wang Gengnian, deputy director of Movie
Bureau of the Ministry of Radio, Film and Television, said.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese official urged more refined films to be produced to
meet the Chinese people's growing demand for more cultural
products.
</P>
<P>
"The films are as good as 'Independence Day' or 'Eraser' in
many aspects except for the tremendous investment in those
American films," film critics said.
</P>
<P>
"What's more important is that the films have what we think are
Chinese qualities," critics added.
</P>
<P>
The films will also help shape China's image in the world film
industry, they said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
