<HEADLINE> Service Quality Framework Set for Phone Operators in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, April 3 (Xinhua) -- The Malaysian government has
set a service quality framework for cellular phone operators in
the country in a bid to reduce consumer complaints.
</P>
<P>
Complete data on each operator would be published annually to
give consumers access to the type of quality service, Minister of
Energy, Telecommunications and Posts Leo Moggie said today after
handing over a framework on monitoring service quality for
cellular phone operators.
</P>
<P>
"This is one way to make the operators sensitive to providing
quality service and give consumers a choice among the various
operators as to which they feel comfortable with," he said.
</P>
<P>
The framework was drawn up after consultation with the
operators and would determine the ranking of their service
quality, he said, adding it would be filled up by them and audited
by the ministry.
</P>
<P>
"We received a lot of complaints from consumers... so we want
to have a common framework by which the services could be
standardized," he said.
</P>
<P>
The framework also proposes the establishment of a Center for
Monitoring Service Quality in Telecommunications to coordinate
monitoring of the standards and service quality in that sector.
</P>
<P>
To meet the increasing demand in the telecommunications sector,
Malaysia plans to invest some 5.2 billion U.S dollars in the
sector during the 2001-2005 period.
</P>
<P>
At present, the population-phone ratio is about 16 percent
which is expected to increase to about 25 percent by the year 2000
and further to 30 percent by the year 2005.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
