<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970403.0108 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaria Tops Other Killers In Tanzania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Malaria is a major public
health problem in Tanzania as it kills between 76,000 to 134,000
people each year, the local paper "Guardian" reported today.
</P>
<P>
The National Malaria Control Program (NMCP) Manager, Alex
Mwita was quoted as saying that the majority of the deaths
affected children especially those under five years and pregnant
women.
</P>
<P>
"Malaria is also an economic drain to the country", said the
NMCP manager, adding that the impact of malaria on the country in
terms of direct and indirect costs accounted for 34.4 percent of
the GNP.
</P>
<P>
Mwita outlined five causative factors of malaria as: malaria
vectors, the type of parasites and drug resistance, environmental
changes and socio-economic and political factors.
</P>
<P>
He further said the malaria vectors found in Tanzania are
comparably more efficient malaria transmitters because they
prefer to bite man to other animals and are endowed with a longer
life span.
</P>
<P>
The type of malaria parasites existing in Tanzania are mostly
"plasmodium falciparum" which do not only cause severe disease
but are also increasingly becoming resistant to the curative
drugs.
</P>
<P>
On the environmental point of view, malaria has invaded
highland areas as a result of deforestation. People in such areas
have little immunity to malaria.
</P>
<P>
"Construction projects have bred more mosquitoes", according
to Mwita.
</P>
<P>
Social, economic and political factors led to an increase of
malaria due to some important policy decisions which led to the
collapse of the urban malaria control services.
</P>
<P>
However, he said there is a new mood of optimism borne out of
a new but simple technology of impregnating fabrics with
pyrethroid group of chemicals.
</P>
<P>
Mwita observed, "research studies done in Tanzania and Gambia
show that the use of nets and other fabrics treated with these
drugs reduces transmission of the disease and the death rate
especially among children". 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
