<HEADLINE> Okinawans Indignant at Government's Land Law Revision </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 3 (Xinhua) -- The leaders and citizens of Japan's
Okinawa Prefecture today expressed indignation at a government
decision to revise a land expropriation law so that compulsory
land leases will be given to the U.S. troops in Japan, according
to a report reaching here.
</P>
<P>
The adoption of the land law revision bill at a special cabinet
meeting early in the day was "truly a pity," Okinawa Governor
Masahide Ota was quoted by Kyodo News Service as saying.
</P>
<P>
Ota called on the Diet (parliament) "to inquire carefully into
the revision in light of the actual conditions in the prefecture
and constitutional principles."
</P>
<P>
Okinawa City Mayor Shusei Arakawa also expressed disappointment
at the cabinet's decision.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Hideaki Ikehara, head of a local anti-war landowners
association also criticized Tokyo for having "jettisoned the
constitutional state" with its unilateral action.
</P>
<P>
The passage of the proposed revision bill would allow the
government to continue leasing land for 12 U.S. military
facilities after the May 14 expiry deadline.
</P>
<P>
The bill is expected to be debated by the House of
Representatives next Monday. 
</P>
