<HEADLINE> Australian Shares Close Higher Buoyed by WBC Merger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 3 (Xinhua) -- The Australian share market
defied a fall on Wall Street to close higher today, buoyed by news
of the proposed Westpac Bank of Melbourne merger and Coca-Cola
Amatil's soft drink deal.
</P>
<P>
Brokers said expectations that the US market would bounce back
also helped investor confidence.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index finished 5.8 points firmer at its high
of 2,361.0.
</P>
<P>
Westpac Bank today launched a 9.75 Australian dollars a share
bid for Bank Of Melbourne, valuing the Victorian regional at 1.435
billion Australian dollars (1.126 billion US dollars).
</P>
<P>
Bank Of Melbourne shares jumped 9.9 percent to all time high
after the merger was made public before easing in the afternoon to
close 70 cents up at 9.50 Australian dollars (7.41 US dollars).
</P>
<P>
The all industrials index rose 7.8 points to 3,689.3, led by
banks and Coca Cola Amatil.
</P>
<P>
The food index jumped 212.5 points to finish at 5,567.0, and
soft drink giant Coca Cola jumped 85 cents today.
</P>
<P>
The all resources index was up 4.5 points at 1,340.2.
</P>
<P>
National turnover totaled 309.34 million shares worth 893.13
million Australian dollars (701.1 million US dollars).  
</P>
