<HEADLINE> World Triathlon Champion Killed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 3 (Xinhua) -- World triathlon champion Judith
Marie Flannery of the United States was killed by a car driven by
an unlicensed 16-year-old boy when she was riding a bicycle on a
road in the Maryland suburbs of Washington on Wdenesday.
</P>
<P>
Flannery, 57, a mother of five, was pronounced dead at the
scene. Flannery was a four-time world triathlon champion and a
six-time U.S. triathlon champion.
</P>
<P>
She was riding uphill with two other cyclists when a car came
down from the other side of the road and crossed the center line,
police said. The car missed the first two bicyclists but struck
Flannery.
</P>
<P>
The boy's father was sitting in the passenger seat at the time
of the accident. Police said the father had been drinking alcohol.
</P>
<P>
They identified the boy as Timothy S. Rinehart of Rockville,
Maryland. His father was identified as Ronald Rinehart.
</P>
<P>
Prosecutors were reviewing the case to decide whether to press
charges.
</P>
<P>
Flannery clinched her fourth world championship last year when
she completed the triathlon's 1.5-kilometer swim, the 40-kilometer
bike ride and the 10-kilometer run in 2 hours, 30 minutes, 46
seconds to win the women's 55-59 age group. 
</P>
</TEXT>
