<HEADLINE> Malaysia to Propose New Law Against Illegal Abortion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Health Minister
Chua Jui Meng said today his ministry is seeking more powers
through a proposed new legislation to enable it to act against
illegal abortion in the country.
</P>
<P>
"At the moment the ministry is fairly limited in action towards
offenses of this nature, unless the powers are enhanced," he said
while commenting on a news report that more pregnant teenagers
were resorting to abortions either through the traditional way or
by medical clinics.
</P>
<P>
The Health Ministry has no task force to carry out spot checks
on premises suspected of carrying out illegal abortions or the
powers to prosecute those involved, he told reporters after
attending the opening of the first Asian International Congress on
Emergency Medicine here.
</P>
<P>
The Malaysian Medical Council (MMC), the body governing
doctors' conduct, could only act against complaints, he said,
adding so far the MMC has never taken any disciplinary action
against doctors for illegal abortion.
</P>
<P>
"Quite often doctors themselves when confronted by law say that
they have good reasons on medical conditions that required an
abortion," he said.
</P>
<P>
The minister said his ministry believed that doctors and
medical professionals were not the best people to be enforcers.
</P>
<P>
"The police for instance would be better enforcers as criminal
abortion falls within the Penal Code," he said.
</P>
<P>
Under the Penal Code only the police could charge suspected
performers of illegal abortions, the minister added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970403.0119 </DOCNO>
