<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Welcomes US Customs' Decision on HK Garment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 3 (Xinhua) -- A spokesman of the Hong Kong
government today welcomed the United States Customs' decision to
remove, with effect from May 1, the single entry bond requirement
on eight categories of Hong Kong garment products since last June.
</P>
<P>
The single entry bond requirement has led to increased costs
and administrative burden to Hong Kong's trade, the spokesman
said.
</P>
<P>
He said "the Hong Kong government will have an effective system
to deal with the problem of illegal transshipment, particularly
with the series of new initiatives that we have introduced in the
past year."
</P>
<P>
He said, "As part of our efforts against illegal transshipment,
cooperation with trading partners has always been important.
</P>
<P>
He said that Hong Kong will continue its efforts in cooperation
with the US and other trading partners to enhance both sides'
effectiveness in the common objective of tackling illegal
transshipment.
</P>
<P>
The US Customs announced on April 2 the outcome of their review
of the additional import measures imposed on certain Hong Kong
garment imports since June 1996.
</P>
<P>
In June 1996, the US Customs imposed a number of additional
import measures on 10 categories of Hong Kong garments, including
dresses, skirts, nightwear, underwear and suits.
</P>
<P>
The measures include additional requirements in import
documentation, the requirement for a single entry bond, and the
requirement for production verification by the US customs in Hong
Kong factories.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong has objected to unilateral imposition of the
additional requirements, pointing out that they are applied to the
relevant products only from Hong Kong and are therefore
discriminatory.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
