<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysian PM to Visit Kuwait, Bahrain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad will visit Kuwait and Bahrain beginning Saturday
to add impetus to bilateral relations between Malaysia and the two
Gulf states, a Foreign Ministry official said here today.
</P>
<P>
The common desire is to develop new avenues for cooperation in
trade and investment and cooperation in third world countries,
Deva Mohamed Ridzam AbdullahIts, under-secretary of the West Asia,
Africa and Organization of Islamic Conference Division of the
ministry, said at a press briefing.
</P>
<P>
Deva said that Mahathir would be in Kuwait for three days at
the invitation of Kuwaiti Crown Prince and Prime Minister Sheikh
Saad Al-Abdulla Al-Sabah before leaving for Bahrain for a
three-day visit at the invitation of Bahraini Prime Minister
Sheikh Khalifa bin Sulman Al-Khalifa.
</P>
<P>
In Kuwait, Mahathir, who is leading a 15-member official
delegation, will visit the Kuwait Liberation Tower, which is the
world's fourth highest telecommunications tower, and the Seif
Palace, the newly-completed government complex which houses the
offices of the state's Emir, the prime minister and the cabinet,
according to the official.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia is expected to sign a double taxation avoidance
agreement with Kuwait during a bilateral meeting scheduled on the
second day of the visit.
</P>
<P>
Deva said Malaysia, which established relations with Kuwait in
1975, had since signed economic and technical cooperation,
cultural and scientific, investment guarantee, trade and air
services agreements with the state.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait Airways flew twice a week to Kuala Lumpur but
temporarily terminated its service last year due to shortage of
aircraft while Malaysia Airlines (MAS) flew to Kuwait as a
stopover en route to London but suspended its flights because of
the Gulf crisis.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait is Malaysia's fifth largest trading partner in West Asia
after the United Arab Emirates, Saudi Arabia, Egypt and Jordan.
Bilateral trade between Malaysia and Kuwait amounted to 296
million ringgit (about 118.4 million U.S. dollars) last year.
</P>
<P>
In Bahrain, apart from a bilateral meeting, Mahathir will also
deliver a keynote address at the Gulf Economic Forum.
</P>
<P>
Bahrain has a highly developed tourism industry. "This offers a
good opportunity for Malaysian banks and the tourism sector in
Malaysia," said Deva.
</P>
<P>
Total trade between Malaysia and Bahrain amounted to about 100
million ringgit (about 40 million dollars) last year with
Malaysia's exports valued at 54 million ringgit (about 21.6
million dollars).
</P>
<P>
Malaysia and Bahrain signed an economic and technical
cooperation agreement and a cultural and scientific cooperation
agreement in 1975 and an air services agreement in 1994, with Gulf
Air flying twice a week to Kuala Lumpur, but MAS no.  
</P>
</TEXT>
