<HEADLINE> Pakistan Minister Appeals More Investment in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Agricultural Minister
Abida Hussain today called on the government to increase the
budgetary allocation to the agricultural sector.
</P>
<P>
"The agricultural sector contributes 24 percent to the national
income whereas it receives less than 5 percent of the development
expenditure each year," said Abida at the "Conference on Pakistani
Agriculture" opened here this morning.
</P>
<P>
Successive governments have treated enhancement of agricultural
production as a bureaucratic exercise of fixing targets without
achieving any meaningful result, she said.
</P>
<P>
"As a result, our country, which once called the food granary
of the sub-continent has become a net food importer with a
shrinking export surplus," she said.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, the yields of all major crops have stagnated and
the leading sources of growth have shifted from crops to livestock
and horticultural crops, she said.
</P>
<P>
In order to increase the agricultural productivity and
production, she said, the government should take effective
measures to protect cultivated land, to renovate irrigation system
and to enhance the agricultural research.
</P>
<P>
The agricultural conference, brought together thousands of
farmer delegates across the country, aims to spell out a dynamic
development strategy for Pakistan's agricultural sector.  
</P>
</TEXT>
