<HEADLINE> Cypriot Doctors Stage 48-Hour Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Doctors at state-run hospitals
in the government-controlled part of Cyprus started a 48-hour
strike this morning in demand for higher salary and pension
reforms.
</P>
<P>
The strike was decided Wednesday by the civil servants trade
union (PASYDY), of which the public hospital doctors are its
members.
</P>
<P>
The PASYDY announced that the strike is caused by a deadlock
in the process to meet the doctors' demands.
</P>
<P>
The union, however, said inpatients as well as
life-threatening cases in hospitals will be treated by a skeleton
staff.
</P>
<P>
PASYDY Secretary General Glafcos Hadjipetrou said Wednesday
that the union decided to proceed with the strike because the
Ministry of Health refused to resume with doctors the dialogue
aimed at reaching a solution.
</P>
<P>
Public hospital doctors went on a 24-hour warning strike on
March 13.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to the PASYDY, Health Minister Manolis
Christofides described the strike measures as "the worst
choice", and said their demands are unlikely to be met under the
pressure of the strike. 
</P>
</TEXT>
