<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Artists Discuss Reform of Peking Opera </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, April 3 (Xinhua) -- A number of Shanghai artists say
that the 200-year-old Peking Opera must be reformed if it is to
survive.
</P>
<P>
At a seminar this month, they criticized some artists for
sticking to old methods and being unwilling to appeal to modern
tastes.
</P>
<P>
Although Beijing was the birthplace of the opera, a delicate
combination of lyrics, music, and acrobatics, Shanghai developed
its own school by changing the opera's original style early in
this century.
</P>
<P>
"The experience of the Shanghai school should be examined,"
said Guo Hancheng, a noted artist, adding, "The nation as a whole
should learn from the Shanghai artists' spirit of exploration and
creativity."
</P>
<P>
Peking Opera faces challenges from modern forms of
entertainment like television and dance, and younger audiences
have drifted away from theater. Some Beijing-based Peking Opera
troupes receive government subsidies.
</P>
<P>
However, while Beijing theaters stagnate, many Shanghai Peking
Opera theaters are flourishing. One reason is that the Shanghai
artists have injected new concepts into the old opera to reflect
modern themes.
</P>
<P>
"The key point is to build a bridge across the gap between the
traditional and modern arts," Guo explained. Artists suggested
that the creation of new repertoires, a reform of management, and
promoting the opera on a commercial scale be emphasized. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
