<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Grasslands in China Enjoy Promising Development Prospect </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HUHHOT, April 3 (Xinhua) -- China's grasslands, the total area
of which ranks second in the world after Australia, are playing a
better part in boosting local economy and improving the
environment.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics show that China has 400 million ha of
natural grasslands which cover two-fifths of the country's land
area, and three-quarters of which are located in pastoral areas.
</P>
<P>
The grasslands in northern and western China are the major
pastoral areas, which mainly accommodate Mongolian, Tibetan, and
Kazak ethnic peoples. For generations, the ethnic groups have been
relying on the grasslands to raise livestock.
</P>
<P>
Now that the central government has decided to step up economic
growth in the country's central and western areas, the grasslands
will boom even more, officials said.
</P>
<P>
Domestic animals such as cattle and sheep mainly live on
grass. In this sense, a large amount of grain can be saved.
Sources with the Ministry of Agriculture said that even though
China's grain production achieves 500 million tons by year 2000,
there will be a want of 60 million tons of feed.
</P>
<P>
The development of animal husbandry can ease the burden of
grain shortage, the sources said. In 1995, the production of
cattle and sheep meat was 6.17 million tons, which equals to about
26 million tons of grain.
</P>
<P>
Grasslands also act as a large vegetation coverage curbing the
spread of deserts. In recent years, the dry-up in some stretches
of the Yellow River, and black windstorms in Xinjiang, Gansu,
Inner Mongolia, and Liaoning are believed to be related to the
deterioration of grasslands.
</P>
<P>
Beginning from the 1990s, the central government has been
putting more money in protecting and improving the grasslands.
Since 1995, the State Planning Commission has set aside 50 million
yuan (six million US dollars) a year to carry out pilot
development projects in the pastoral areas in northern China,
doubling the central government's investment in the sector. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970403.0137 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South China's First Multi-Purpose Ag-Development Center </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANTOU, April 3 (Xinhua) -- A comprehensive agricultural group
that combines the functions of research, production, and sales was
recently set up in Chaozhou city, in south China's Guangdong
province.
</P>
<P>
The Chaozhou Agricultural Technology Development Center is the
first of its kind in Guangdong province.
</P>
<P>
The company has spent 10.6 million yuan (1.3 million US
dollars) on a research building, a model farm for
ecologically-sound agriculture, a peacock breeding farm, a
compound fertilizer plant, and a company for spreading the use of
agricultural technology. 
