<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Overseas Banks Become Part of Special Zone's Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, April 3 (Xinhua) -- The overseas financial sector in
Shenzhen, China's first special economic zone, has become a
regular part of the city's financial system.
</P>
<P>
A total of 15 billion US dollars has been channeled into the
city's industries by overseas bank branches since 1987. In 1996
alone, they brought in 2.45 billion US dollars, accounting for
more than half of the influx of overseas capital.
</P>
<P>
They have also provided financial innovations, giving Shenzhen
offshore financial services, Automatic Teller Machine services,
syndicate loans, and loans backed by mortgages.
</P>
<P>
In 1982, the first overseas bank branch was opened in the
special economic zone. Since then, assets of overseas financial
institutions have been growing at a rate of 14 percent to 5.3
billion US dollars at the end of last year, almost 25 percent of
the total capital of Shenzhen's financial sector. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970403.0139 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Forestry Vital to Human Existence: Lawmaker </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 3 (Xinhua) -- The importance of forestry should
be understood as not only preserving the environment, but human
existence, a senior Chinese lawmaker said here today.
</P>
<P>
"Economic and social development calls for our attention and
concrete efforts to protect the forest reserves, and the
conditions for human existence," said Wang Binqian, vice-chairman
of the Standing Committee of the National People's Congress (NPC).
</P>
<P>
He issued the call at a conference on starting a inspection
campaign on the compliance of the country's Forest Law organized
by the top legislature, the NPC.
</P>
<P>
Three groups will be sent to Jiangxi, Fujian and Yunnan
provinces in a few days. Other provinces, autonomous regions, and
municipalities are asked to conduct self-examinations and to
submit reports to the NPC.
</P>
<P>
"Environment and development are issues of common concern in
the world, and the World Conference on Environment and Development
in 1992 declared that forestry conservation is the key issue of
the environment," Wang said.
</P>
<P>
He said that China has paid great attention to the forestry
development and has taken a series of measures, one of which is
the promulgation and enforcement of the Forestry Law in 1984 and
1985.
</P>
<P>
The law has played an important role in protecting, developing,
and making rational use of forest reserves, Wang said.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics, 12 provinces, autonomous regions, and
municipalities have greened all their barren hills and wastelands
suitable for growing trees.
</P>
<P>
China's forest area has increased from 115 million ha in the
early 1980s to the current 133.7 million ha; timber stock volume,
from 10.26 billion cubic meters to 11.785 billion cubic meters;
and forest coverage rate, from 12 percent to 13.92 percent.
</P>
<P>
The country has increased both forest area and timber stock
volume, while worldwide forest resources are declining.
</P>
<P>
However, Wang pointed out that China remains a country short of
forest. It faces serious ecological problems such as the shortage
of forest resources, serious water and soil erosion,
desertification, shortage of water, frequent occurrence of floods,
droughts, typhoons, and other disasters.
</P>
<P>
All those problems indicate that the ecological condition in
China has posed a major bottle-neck factor for the country's
economic and social development, the senior legislator said.
</P>
<P>
According to Minister of Forestry Xu Youfang, the country's per
capita forest area and forest stock volume are only 15 percent and
12 percent of the world level, and forest coverage rate per head
is no more than half of the world level.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, 18.7 percent of the national land, or 1.794 million
square kilometers, is suffering from soil erosion; direct economic
losses resulted from natural disasters exceed 200 billion yuan a
year.
</P>
<P>
Wang said the law enforcement inspection efforts aim to sum up
experiences, seek solutions to problems, and to promote the forest
renewal.
</P>
<P>
"This has not only shown our attention to environment and
development, it is also one of the most important realistic
measures to solve the problems," Wang added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970403.0140 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
