<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Women's Showing More Political Might </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 3 (Xinhua) -- The number of women officials in
China was 13.28 million by the end of last year, almost 200 times
the number in 1949, when modern China was founded.
</P>
<P>
Women officials now account for 38.8 percent of the Chinese
officials, sources from the All-China Women's Federation (ACWF)
say, and in 31 municipalities, provinces, and autonomous regions
there are women in provincial level positions.
</P>
<P>
There are women in all county leading bodies across China and
women constitute over half of China's villages and towns in 15
municipalities, provinces, and autonomous regions.
</P>
<P>
Enrollments of school-age girls reached 98.63 percent in 1996,
1.65 percentage points higher than in 1992. During the Eighth
Five-Year Plan (1991-1995) period, an additional 1.1 million women
gained literacy and 96 million women got practical technological
training.
</P>
<P>
The ACWF source says she attributes the progress to the Law on
the Protection of Women's Rights and Interests which went into
effect on October 1, 1992.
</P>
<P>
"Women's living and working conditions have improved
distinctly since governments at all levels fully protected women's
rights and interests in accordance with laws," the source says.
</P>
<P>
Women's right to work was further guaranteed when an additional
1.7 million women were employed from 1992 to 1995, increasing the
number of women workers to 57.55 million by 1995.
</P>
<P>
Last year alone, comprehensive social security has provided
over one million women workers with maternity subsidies and
medical costs.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, governments at various levels have been cracking down
on the abduction and selling of women and children and on
prostitution. Crimes in violation of women's rights are coming
under control, the source said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970403.0142 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Railway Spurs Development in Southwest China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIHAI, April 3 (Xinhua) -- The Nanning-Kunming Railway, the
rail artery in southwest China that went into operation last
month, has brought new opportunities to the development of the
coastal area in Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
The new railway will demand that the cargo handling volume of
Fangcheng Port, the region's largest, to grow two million tons
each year, prompting a major expansion of the port's capacity,
said Ye Shixiang, director of the port authorities.
</P>
<P>
He said construction of the 13.5-million-yuan No.0 berth has
been completed, while that of the No.9 and No.10 will start within
the year.
</P>
<P>
Ye added that the existing water courses will be dredged to
ensure that 30,000-tonnage ships can enter the port at any time,
and the capacity of the storing grounds will be enlarged from the
current 700,000 tons to 1.5 million tons.
</P>
<P>
The price of the stocks of Xinli company, whose biggest
shareholder is the Beihai Port, surged from six to 15 yuan on
March 18, the day when the Nanning-Kunming railway went into
operation.
</P>
<P>
Yue Zhiwei, director of the Beihai Port Authorities, said the
price surge showed investors' boosting confidence in the future of
the port.
</P>
<P>
For the Japanese Marubeni Corp., the railway will help cut down
the cost of its processing operations in China, said a company
official.
</P>
<P>
Marubeni has built a special dock for liquid sulfur at
Fangcheng port, which will be shipped by the Nanning-Kunming
Railway to Kunming for processing, and the end products will be
shipped back to Fangcheng for export.
</P>
<P>
Three other companies from the inlands areas and Hong Kong have
also invested more than 100 million yuan in building their own
wharves at the port.
</P>
<P>
The Nanning-Kunming Railway will greatly promote industries,
transportation, tourism, commerce and trade in the coastal area of
Guangxi and bring a new wave of expansion, concurred experts who
attended a symposium on China's development in the next century
held in Beihai in late March.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
