<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya to Set up Crime Research Center </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 3 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government is
scheduled to establish a crime research center following
increasing incidents of crime in country.
</P>
<P>
In a Kenya Gazette supplement, Kenyan Attorney-General Amos
Wako published the National Crime Research Center Bill to be
tabled to the current session of the parliament for enactment.
</P>
<P>
According to the bill, the center will evaluate causes and
come up with preventive measures to the crimes which are
threatening the security of the society and to life and property
of the people.
</P>
<P>
The center will also serve as a centralized source of
information to agencies of government responsible for the
administration of criminal justice.
</P>
<P>
It will disseminate its research findings through mass media
with a view to enhancing the awareness of related agencies and
the community on crime prevention and the rehabilitation of
criminal offenders.
</P>
<P>
Early last month, the Kenyan police set up a mobile unit with
modern equipment to combat escalating crimes like armed robberies
in the country.
</P>
<P>
The new unit is using specially designed land rovers and act
as a special rapid deployment force to preempt car thefts, bank
robberies and other crimes.
</P>
<P>
The mobile unit is being deployed in Nairobi, Mombasa, Kisumu,
Nakuru, Eldoret, Kiambu and Thika, and in bandit-prone areas in
the east African country.
</P>
<P>
According to a latest police report, armed crime incidents in
Kenya's capital Nairobi had risen to 470 in the third quarter of
last year compared with 331 and 373 in the first and second
quarters.
</P>
<P>
Car-hijackings in the capital had reached an all-time high of
420 incidents for a three-month period ending last September, up
from 227 and 201 in the first two quarters last year.
</P>
<P>
In February, about 1.7 million U.S. Dollars were robbed by
gunmen at a branch of the Standard Chartered Bank in the capital
and one million Dollars was casually stolen from the Embakasi
strongroom of Kenya Freight Handling Ltd.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan Police Commissioner Duncan Wachira was quoted as saying
that as criminals have become sophisticated, the police need
modern equipment to cope with the criminals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
