<DOCNO> XIE19970403.0146 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's New Measure To Protect Intellectual Property Rights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 3 (Xinhua) -- China will adopt a new measure to
protect the intellectual property rights, according to Song Jian,
state councillor and minister in charge of the State Science and
Technology Commission.
</P>
<P>
Song said at a national conference in Beijing today that the
measure is meant to improve Chinese products' competitive ability
on the international market. He explained that the number of
patents applied for by all Chinese enterprises in a year is
smaller than that for even one big foreign company.
</P>
<P>
Some well-known Chinese trademarks are even registered for
patents by foreigners, he noted, and therefore, "We are losing a
great share of the international market."
</P>
<P>
The high-profile conference has selected 45 enterprises and
institutes fo an experiment where the government helps them set up
special IPR affairs departments, create IPR protection networks,
and build a self-protection system.
</P>
<P>
These 45 include major oil and chemical corporations, computer
companies, and prestigious universities and scientific research
institutes for whom IPR are especially important.
</P>
<P>
Observers say that the measures signal a beginning of
activities that raise IPR protection in China to a higher level.
</P>
<P>
In the past few years, the country has adopted many measures to
crack down on copyright piracy, including the closing of
commercial video halls nationwide, checks on the market,
promulgating more laws, and sending more culprits to jail.
</P>
<P>
The most noteworthy event was the seizing of 29 underground CD
production lines in Guangdong province recently. Those who
provided tips in the case were given a reward of 300,000 yuan
(37,000 US dollars) each.
</P>
<P>
All the crackdowns have benefited foreign business interests,
said Shen Rengan, deputy director of the State Copyright
Administration, adding that the main purpose of China's IPR
protection, in fact, is boosting its own industry, science, and
culture.
</P>
<P>
"In the planned economy, it was not important for a company to
protect its IPR, because all resources and products were
controlled by the state," noted Xu Guanhua, deputy minister of the
State Science and Technology Commission.
</P>
<P>
"But in the market economy, IPR protection has become a
strategic issue for a company, and an urgent problem faced by the
country, which is seeking to be a part of the international
scene," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics, in 1996 Chinese enterprises and
institutes applied for 25,126 patents. In some high-technology
fields, such as electronics, medicine, communications, and the
chemical and aerospace industries, foreign patent applications
account for as much as 80 or even 90 percent of the total number
of applications in China.
</P>
<P>
And, in the past 10 years, Chinese companies have applied for
only 2,000 patents in foreign countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970403.0147 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Exiled Albanian King Set to Leave S. Africa for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Deposed King Leka I of
Albania is preparing to leave South Africa for home after more
than half a century in exile, local daily "The Citizen" quoted
his secretariat as reporting today.
</P>
<P>
As the Albanian government had authorized his return, Leka I
could return when he likes, a representative of the Johannesburg
based court said.
</P>
<P>
However, no precise date had yet been fixed for King Leka to
go home, the unidentified representative said.
</P>
<P>
The royal court said that 10 Albanian political parties had
backed the idea of authorizing Leka's return at a working meeting
on March 28 called by the new transitional government's Prime
Minister Bashkim Fino.
</P>
<P>
King Leka inherited the Albanian crown in 1961 on the death of
his father King Zog I, who was proclaimed king in 1928, 16 years
after the former Ottoman province became autonomous.
</P>
<P>
The monarch, who has lived in England, France and Spain, moved
to South Africa with his family in the early 1980s. He has
devoted himself to politics in recent years and prepared for the
restoration of monarchy in Albania. 
</P>
</TEXT>
