<HEADLINE> Ugandan Army to Fight TB </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, April 3 (Xinhua) -- The Ugandan army decided to train
its medical personnel to fight against tuberculosis (TB), local
weekly "The People" reported today.
</P>
<P>
The resolution was made at the end of a three-day workshop on
TB control, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Francis Adatu-Engwau, national TB/leprosy program manager,
assured army medical personnel that the government will assistant
them with training and providing with equipment such as
microscopes, slides, reagents and drugs.
</P>
<P>
Sam Lwanga, director of medical services in the army, appealed
to the officers to continuously monitor, and supervise the
patients to ensure they take proper dosages of drugs.
</P>
<P>
Medical personnel of all four divisions of the Ugandan army
take part in the workshop.
</P>
<P>
TB is a common communicable disease in Africa. Some reports
said a quarter of African people have TB. 
</P>
