<DOCNO> XIE19970403.0159 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Cabinet Gives Green Light For U.S. Land Use </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 3 (Xinhua) -- The Japanese government Thursday
approved a bill at a special meeting to give the green light for
the continued land use by the U.S. military forces in Okinawa, a
southern island of Japan.
</P>
<P>
The bill, which has been submitted to the parliament, said,
"the leased land, whose formalities of the use right have not been
completed before the end of the expiry, can be used continuously
after the guarantee for compensation is provided."
</P>
<P>
The Japanese government would be illegally occupying the land
in Okinawa if the existing law is not revised, as the May 14
deadline on expiry of leases on private land used for
U.S. military facilities on the island is approaching.
</P>
<P>
The bill was strongly opposed by the Social Democratic Party
and Okinawa residents.
</P>
<P>
However, the cabinet and the ruling Liberal Democratic Party
are determined to revise the bill, which is to legalize the
continuous lease of land by the U.S. forces.
</P>
<P>
"We have a responsibility to provide bases and facilities for
the U.S. military as part of the Japanese government's obligation
under the U.S.-Japan Security Treaty," said Prime Minister Ryutaro
Hashimoto, who had asked parliament to approve the bill.
</P>
<P>
The bill, which is to be discussed in the House of
Representatives on Friday, is expected to be passed on April 11
and be enacted on April 18, six days before Hashimoto's visit to
the United States.
</P>
<P>
Some 3,000 landowners in Okinawa had refused to go on leasing
land to the U.S. forces under the Japanese anti-U.S. sentiments,
which was heightened after the rape of an Okinawa school girl by
three U.S. servicemen in September 1995.
</P>
<P>
So far, about 27,000 of the 47,000 U.S. troops in Japan are in
Okinawa, which accommodates 75 percent of the U.S. installations
in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
