<DOCNO> XIE19970403.0160 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Attempts to Divide Tibet Will Fail: Tibetan Scholars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, April 3 (Xinhua) -- A group of Tibetan sociologists has
denounced the collaboration of Taiwan authorities with the Dalai
Lama and his followers in their attempt to split the motherland.
</P>
<P>
Puncog Cering, president of the Tibetan Academy of Social
Sciences, said that although Taiwan authorities held to the
position that Tibet is an inseparable part of China for more than
four decades, Taiwan's present leadership, since coming to power,
has not only voiced support for the Dalai Lama's so-called
"five-point peaceful plan" for achieving "independence of Tibet",
but has openly invited the Dalai Lama to Taiwan and has approved
the institution of an office in Taiwan for the Dalai Lama's clique.
</P>
<P>
"Under the disguise of religion and culture," he noted, "the
Taiwan authorities and the Dalai Lama's clique have increased
their collusion, but it is actually a last-ditch, vain attempt by
separatists on the eve of Hong Kong's return to the motherland."
</P>
<P>
"Their plot to split the motherland will never succeed," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Xini Cering, deputy director of the Academy's Research
Institute on Religion, cited the Dalai Lama as the chieftain of
the old Tibetan regime, which combined political and religious
authorities.
</P>
<P>
"It is a well-known fact that during his reign, Tibet was a
backwater area in terms of science, technology, culture, and
education, and the serfs there had no personal freedom to speak
of," he explained.
</P>
<P>
Since the Dalai Lama's attempt to split the nation was thwarted
in 1959, the religious scholar said, the Dalai Lama has all along
engaged in separatist activities, and "What he actually wants is
to bring serfdom back to Tibet."
</P>
<P>
He added that the collaboration of Taiwan authorities with
the Dalai Lama's clique is in fact one of backers of "Taiwan
independence" and backers of "Tibetan independence", and that
their goal is the separation of the motherland.
</P>
<P>
In the more than 40 years since the peaceful liberation of
Tibet, especially in the 18 years since China adopted its reform
and opening-up policies, experts said, the emancipated serfs have
seen great social and economic development, and an improvement in
their standard of living.
</P>
<P>
"The Tibetan people are in firm opposition to activities by the
Taiwan authorities and the Dalai clique to sabotage national
unity, which go against the tide of history," the experts said.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
