<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Spells out Investment Goals for 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 3 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government said
today that it has spelled out its investment goals for 1997, which
aim to achieve a 17 percent increase in investment over last year.
</P>
<P>
Investments in the Philippines last year rose to 490 billion
pesos (18.6 billion U.S. dollars), an increase of 20 percent over
the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The government attributed the increase to the favorable
investment climate in the country and the surging economy, which
grew 6.8 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
In a statement released here today, the government said that
with more domestic and foreign investment this year, it will try
to "spread prosperity, disperse industry in the countryside,
enhance global competitiveness of the nation's agriculture and
industry, increase exports, open up opportunities for small and
medium enterprises and build up infrastructure."
</P>
<P>
It said that this year's investment priorities plan contains 32
areas of preferred economic activities, including export
industries, manufacturing, agriculture, food and forestry,
textiles, chemical products, infrastructure development,
environment protection and mining, it said.
</P>
<P>
Of the 32 areas, the government said, 28 are carried over from
the 1996 plan. The four new inclusions are feeds production, pulp
and paper, book publishing and fish production, it said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
