<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-03 07:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Pressing Israel to Suspend Har Homa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 3 (Xinhua) -- The United States is
pressing Israel to suspend the controversial Har Homa housing
project as a good-will gesture to salvage the peace process,
Israel Radio reported today.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted Israeli sources as saying that Israel had
received information that the U.S. government would ask Israel
to freeze the Har Homa construction for six months in order
to rebuild confidence between Israel and the Palestinian
National Authority (PNA).
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton, now working to restart the
stalled peace talks, is expected to put forward the demand
to Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu during the latter's
visit to Washington next Monday.
</P>
<P>
Top on the agenda of the Clinton-Netanyahu summit are
finding ways to ease the current tension and violence so to
resume the Israeli-Palestinian negotiations. But Israel expects
the summit to focus on its demand on the PNA's long-term
commitment to fighting terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the U.S. State Department has denied that Clinton
was arranging a three-way summit between Clinton. Netanyahu and
PNA President Yasser Arafat. The announcement was made in
reaction to the statements by Arafat's spokesman Marwan Kanafani
which confirmed that Washington was making efforts to arrange
a three-way summit.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu dismissed Wednesday that notion that the U.S.
government had called him to Washington in order to pressure
him to make gestures or concessions. He stressed there was a
"deep understanding" between Israel and the U.S. on "the
crucial need to reestablish the war against terrorism and the
need for the PNA to keep its commitments."
</P>
<P>
During his brief stay in Washington, Netanyahu is also
scheduled to hold talks with Jordanian King Hussein who is
currently on an official visit.
</P>
<P>
The monarch continued criticizing Netanyahu's policies for
threatening to torpedo the peace process, despite the tragedy
occurring last month near the Israeli-Jordanian border, in which
a Jordanian soldier killed seven Israeli schoolgirls and wounded
six others. Israel blamed the incident on the king's harsh
criticism of Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
Israel is reportedly proposing moving the Israeli-Palestinian
peace process into the "fast track" on the final-status talks,
which it hopes to conclude within six months instead of two
years. But the Palestinian side is deeply suspicious about the
Israeli initiative, citing the lack of its trust on the
Netanyahu government.
</P>
<P>
Under the Oslo accords, the final-status talks, which will
tackle the most difficult issues of final borders, status of
Jerusalem and fate of Palestinian refugees, should be concluded
by May 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
