<DOCNO> XIE19970403.0166 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-03 07:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Most Israelis Reportedly Support Founding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 3 (Xinhua) -- A majority of Jewish Israelis
support the establishment of a Palestinian state, reported The
Jerusalem Post today, quoting a Tel Aviv University survey as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The poll also indicated that an even larger majority believe
the chances of another Arab-Israeli war are very high.
</P>
<P>
Asked whether they support the establishment of a Palestinian
state, if this removed the main obstacle to a real peace between
the Israelis and the Palestinians, 51.3 percent of them said
yes, 44.2 percent said no, and 4.5 percent were non-commital.
</P>
<P>
The telephone poll of 503 Jewish adults, conducted Sunday,
is believed to have a margin of error of 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
Other results show an 8-percent drop in the opinion that the
peace process will bear fruit, and a 6-percent decrease in those
who support the Oslo process (from 54.1 percent to 48 percent).
</P>
<P>
Some 36 percent said they do not believe there is a strong
probability of war between Israel and the Arabs, while 59
percent said the chances are very high.
</P>
<P>
Seventy-four percent said they are concerned about the
possibility that they or their families might become victims of
terrorist attacks, while 26 percent are not worried.
</P>
<P>
On the internal front, the support for a national unity
government is on the increase. About 61 percent back the idea.
</P>
<P>
The poll was conducted against the background of a deepening
crisis over Israeli-Arab relations stemming from the Israeli
construction of a new Jewish settlement at Har Homa in East
Jerusalem, a section regarded by the Palestinians as the capital
of the future Palestinian state. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
