<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Former Pan Africanist
Congress (PAC) president Clarence Makwetu is to appear before an
internal disciplinary committee in Pretoria on three charges of
violating the party's constitution.
</P>
<P>
Senior PAC member Magole Mphahlele will act as prosecutor in
the hearing. The disciplinary committee will be headed by an
Eastern Cape attorney and several other party members, reported a
local newspaper "The Star".
</P>
<P>
Makwetu, now PAC's national chairman, had indicated that he
would call several witnesses at the hearing, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The charges relate to allegations that Makwetu had divided the
party, created factions and had violated the PAC's oath of
allegiance.
</P>
<P>
Makwetu lost the presidency to former Methodist Bishop Stanley
Mogoba at the PAC's national conference in Northern Province last
December.
</P>
<P>
However, Makwetu's supporters claim the elections were
unconstitutional and have refused to recognize the party's new
leadership, thus causing an internal strife and rival factions.
