<DOCNO> XIE19970403.0173 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Retail Sector To Remain Prosperous </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai, the leading commercial
center in China, will enjoy a steady retail market in the second
quarter of this year, according to local government predictions.
</P>
<P>
They say that the improving macro-economic environment and
increased buying power mean that sales will increase during the
period.
</P>
<P>
The local government says that increasing fixed assets
investment, an improved investment structure, and an increased
sales to production ratio indicate a favorable environment.
</P>
<P>
Investment in fixed assets amounted to nearly 9.9 billion yuan
during the first two months of this year, up 44 percent from the
same period in 1996, according to official statistics.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 30 new supermarkets opened in the first three months,
bringing the number of such markets to more than 820. In addition
to large supermarkets, various chain stores in residential areas
are likely to become a new driving force behind commercial
development.
</P>
<P>
With the improved economic climate, purchasing power has
increased. Salary increased at the beginning of the year, and
government policies for re-employment improved incomes.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai's special position as a commercial city will also mean
many visitors from other parts of the country and the world, which
will stimulate the retail market.
</P>
<P>
The local government also pointed to some disadvantages, such
as changing consumer trends in the bond and stock market, and poor
performance of traditional industries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970403.0174 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bright Prospect Predicted for Sino-Polish Economic Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 3 (Xinhua) -- A Beijing-based Polish diplomat
predicts great potential for continual growth in Sino-Polish
economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
In an article published on the Economic and Trade Briefs of the
Embassy Association, Dr. Janusz Fajkowski, the commercial
counsellor of the Polish embassy, said great changes have occured
in bilateral economic ties in recent years.
</P>
<P>
The 340-million-dollar export credit agreement signed between
Poland and China last year, he pointed out, has facilitated the
export of Polish goods to China.
</P>
<P>
In terms of conventions, Dr. Fajkowski added, bilateral
economic ties have already had a solid foundation, "with a series
of agreements at different levels connecting Poland and China."
</P>
<P>
The counsellor pointed out that direct investment in each
country remains limited, however.
</P>
<P>
"Poland has found important, prospective, and interested
economic partners in China," he noted, "while China also views
Poland as a market for future expansion, which may serve as a base
for extension to the European Union market and other eastern
European countries."
</P>
<P>
He mentioned that both Polish and Chinese businesses have
increasing interest in launching joint ventures, and the
operations of Polish businesses are extending from traditional
commercial centers like Shanghai and Guangzhou to other coastal
cities, and central and western China with relatively less
competition.
</P>
<P>
In 1995 and 1996, six Chinese provinces and one autonomous
region established cooperative ties with Polish counterparts, to
promote economic cooperation between the two countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
