<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese, Thai Foreign Ministers Hold Talks in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice-Premier and Foreign
Minister Qian Qichen and Thai Foreign Minister Prachuab Chaiyasarn
welcomed today the promotion of mutual trust, comprehensive
contacts, and cooperation in various fields among the countries in
this region.
</P>
<P>
They stressed that every country's affairs should be decided
independently, and regional affairs should be handled through
consultations at an equal footing by countries in the region,
adding that the outer world should respect the choices made by
countries of the region.
</P>
<P>
Qian said that China always holds that problems and disputes
existing between countries should be settled properly through
peaceful negotiations. Prachuab agreed with and welcomed this.
</P>
<P>
The two foreign ministers spoke highly of the role of the
ASEAN's regional forum in enhancing mutual trust among countries
in the region and safeguarding regional security.
</P>
<P>
They said they hoped to strengthen exchanges and cooperation
within the framework of the ASEAN's regional forum, so as to make
concerted efforts to maintain the lasting peace and stability of
the region.
</P>
<P>
On Asia-Europe meeting, Qian said that both the first
Asia-Europe meeting held in Bangkok one year ago and the
Asia-Europe foreign ministers' meeting held in Singapore recently
had achieved positive results.
</P>
<P>
Hoping that momentum will continue, Qian said that Asian and
European countries can conduct exchanges and dialogs, on the basis
of equality and mutual respect, on many aspects at the Asia-Europe
meeting, while the emphasis still should be put on economic
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Prachuab said Thailand agrees with China's attitude toward the
Asia-Europe meeting, adding that Thailand and China can further
cooperate in this regard.
</P>
<P>
Briefing each other on their foreign relations, the two foreign
ministers reached common understanding on facilitating personnel
exchanges between Hong Kong and Thailand after Hong Kong's return
to the motherland, on bilateral cooperation in cracking down on
international crimes and drug trafficking, and on shipping
cooperation between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Prachuab is here accompanying Thai Prime Minister Chavalit
Yongchaiyudh on a China visit.
</P>
<P>
This morning, trade, communications, industries and mining
ministers of China and Thailand held talks respectively. 
</P>
</TEXT>
