<BODY>
<HEADLINE> East China's No Chimney Industrial Park </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 3 (Xinhua) -- East China's Wuxi New Area, in the
suburb of Jiangsu Province's booming Wuxi City, has an industrial
park without a chimney.
</P>
<P>
"Keep our sky blue, and say farewell to chimneys!" is a slogan
of the new area government.
</P>
<P>
Since the establishment of the industrial park in 1992, the
area has attached great importance to environmental protection,
and refused nearly one billion US dollars of foreign investment
because of pollution problems, according to the head of the local
environment department.
</P>
<P>
The park has spent some 200 million yuan (about 25 million
dollars) in a heat and power plant, and equipped it with advanced
gas and dust treatment facilities.
</P>
<P>
In early 1995, the park began to provide heat and power for
enterprises, and many foreign-funded firms dismantled their own
boilers.
</P>
<P>
The park, with some 200 overseas-backed enterprises and an
annual output value of 10 billion yuan, has met the top government
standard in combating air pollution, according to statistics.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the local government has spent three million yuan
in a sewage discharge system, and will invest some 150 million
yuan in the construction of a large waste water treatment plant.
</P>
<P>
"A clean environment is an advantage in attracting investment,"
said Ding Puren, a leading official of the new area government,
holding that environment cannot be sacrificed for economic
development.
</P>
<P>
"One important reason for our investment in the park is that it
has a clean environment, and the local government's efforts to
combat pollution has enhanced our confidence for the future here,"
said a Swedish investor who established a factory in the park
three years ago with an investment of 18 million dollars, and has
decided to invest another 30 million dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
