<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Saudi Soccer Players Escape Punishment over Drug Failures </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Three players from Saudi
Arabia who failed drug tests at the Asian Cup last December will
not be disciplined, Asian Football Confederation (AFC) general
secretary Peter Velappan said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Velappan said the International Football Federation (FIFA) had
decided not to ban the players, despite the positive tests,
because of "discrepancies in the execution of the doping control."
</P>
<P>
But the Asian governing body still issued a "stern" warning to
all member countries about drug taking.
</P>
<P>
The three players, who have not been named, were among four
Saudis tested after the semi-finals and final of the Cup in the
United Arab Emirates. The Saudis won the final after a penalty
shootout with the hosts.
</P>
<P>
The AFC had originally said four players failed tests.
</P>
<P>
News that no action would be taken came only hours after Saudi
Arabia were named Asian football team of the year at the AFC's
annual awards. 
</P>
</TEXT>
