<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Beaten in FIFA Soccer Vote </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Japan, co-host of the 2002
World Cup finals, lost a bid to secure a seat on the International
Football Federation executive here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Japan Football Association president Saburo Kawabuchi was
beaten by four votes by Worawi Makudi of Thailand in an Asian
Football Confederation (AFC) election for Asia's fourth seat on
the world governing body executive.
</P>
<P>
It was another major defeat for Japan in football power
broking. Not even the support of FIFA vice president Chung Mong
Joon and his Korean counterparts could get the seat for
Kawabuchi. Japan and South Korea, longtime sporting rivals, are
jointly hosting the 2002 finals.
</P>
<P>
Worawi won the backing of Southeast Asian nations which held 10
of the 38 votes at the AFC special congress. With support from
Arab nations, the Thai football chief won by 21 votes to 17.
</P>
<P>
The seat Worawi won will become vacant again at the FIFA
congress in France next June and Japan has said it will be looking
to win it then.
</P>
<P>
Other elections saw China's Zhang Jilong replace deceased
compatriot Xu Fang as an AFC vice president. Iraq defeated Hong
Kong and Iran to gain a seat on the AFC executive. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
