<HEADLINE> Albania's Opposition Decides to Return to Parliament </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Albania's Socialist Party, the
country's largest opposition party, today decided to return to
parliament which it had boycotted since July last year.
</P>
<P>
Namik Kokli, member of the presidium of the Socialist Party,
told reporters that his party made the decision as a show of
support for the national reconciliation government under current
difficult situations, so as to contribute to the country's
recovering from chaos and crisis.
</P>
<P>
The current 140-seat parliament was established last July. The
ruling party, the Democratic Party, held 122 seats, while the
Socialist Party had 10, with the remaining eight seats shared
by the other three small parties.
</P>
<P>
However, the Socialist Party has never recognized the
parliament's legality, accusing the Democratic Party of
manipulating parliamentary elections. 
</P>
</TEXT>
