<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Mt. Anak Krakatau Erupts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Mount Anak Krakatau in the Sunda
Strait, Indonesia, about 300 kilometers west of Jakarta, has been
spewing volcanic ash and rocks for the past few days, an official
said.
</P>
<P>
Gede Suantika, an official of the Meteorology and Geophysics
Agency, said Wednesday that the 200-meter volcano's activity began
to subside at 2:00 p.m. Wednesday but advised that people should
stay away.
</P>
<P>
Anak Krakatau was formed beneath the Sunda strait in 1927 on
the same fault line as Mount Krakatau, which erupted in 1883
creating tidal waves that killed most of the 36,000 people in the
eruption.
</P>
<P>
Reportedly, Mt. Anak Krakatau had erupted every hour in the
past few days and can be heard from Merak Beach, Labuan and
Pandeglang in West Java as well as Kalianca and coastal areas in
Lampung.
</P>
<P>
The local authorities had issued warnings to visitors and
fishermen, telling them not to land at Anak Krakatau or come
within a five-kilometer radius.
</P>
<P>
Meteorology and geophysics officials have warned that the
current level of activity may continue for months.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, activity at Krakatau prompted the authorities to put
the volcano off limits to tourists and climbers for several
months.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970403.0191 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Experts Call for Protection of Kanchenjunga Ecosystem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Environmental experts from
Nepal, India and China have called on their governments to prepare
groundwork to declare the Kanchenjunga mountain ecosystem as a
protected area by 2000, a press release said here today.
</P>
<P>
According to the press release issued by the World Wildlife
Fund (WWF) Nepal Program, participants at a three-day workshop on
the "Conservation of the Kanchenjunga Ecosystem" concluding here
Wednesday urged each of the countries to devise policies and
projects to conserve, maintain and enrich the ecological,
socio-cultural and economic integrity in the area.
</P>
<P>
The 8,568-meter Mt. Kanchenjunga, the third highest in the
world, is located in the border area of Nepal, India and China.
</P>
<P>
About 20 experts including government officials and
environmentalists from the three countries took part in the
workshop jointly organized by the WWF and the Kathmandu-based
International Center for Integrated Mountain Development (ICIMOD).
</P>
<P>
The participants called for the establishment of a Kanchenjunga
Mountain Ecosystem Forum involving officials and experts of the
three countries by November this year to give "greater momentum to
ongoing efforts".
</P>
<P>
They also recommended to hold a regional planning workshop by
March 1998 to identify ways of developing and documenting
information regarding the proposed protected area, the press
release said.
</P>
<P>
Rich in habitat and botanical diversity, the Kanchenjunga
region is also home to several endangered wildlife species like
the snow leopard, musk deer and Himalayan black bear, according to
the WWF press release.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970403.0192 </DOCNO>
