<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, April 3 (Xinhua) -- India will not allow foreign
airlines to hold equity directly or indirectly in any domestic
airline, The Hindustan Times said today.
</P>
<P>
The decision, made by the cabinet on Tuesday, has effectively
sealed the fate of a 23 billion rupee (about 657 million U.S.
dollars) joint venture between India's famous Tata company and
Singapore Airline which had proposed to start a domestic airline
in India.
</P>
<P>
The controversial joint venture project, proposed as early as
in February 1995, envisaged induction of seven new aircraft in the
first year of operation and gradually going up to a fleet of 19
aircraft.
</P>
<P>
But the proposal received strong opposition from the Indian
Civil Aviation Ministry which insisted that foreign airlines
should not be allowed to hold any stake in any domestic airline.
</P>
