<HEADLINE> Dhaka to Arrest Accused Involved in Share Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Some teams of police have been sent
to arrest the persons sued by the Securities and Exchange
Commission (SEC), for manipulation as well as fraudulent acts in
securities trading that led to the recent crash in the capital
market of Dhaka, police sources said here today.
</P>
<P>
Earlier on Wednesday, the SEC, regulator of Bangladesh's
capital market, has filed criminal cases against 42 persons of 15
listed companies and brokerage firms on charges of manipulating
share prices through fraudulent means during a bull run last year.
</P>
<P>
Attorney General K S Nabi and M Zahir, counsel for the SEC,
filed the cases with the chief metropolitan magistrate's court on
the basis of a report by a committee that probed the biggest ever
share market scam in Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the big issuers and share dealers-brokers
including the stock exchange leaders were involved in manipulating
shares during August to December last year.
</P>
<P>
The all share price index in the Dhaka Stock Exchange, which
was 959.05 on June 30, 1996, soared to 3627.01 on November 16,
1996. Experts smelt foulplay by a section of market operators and
sponsors of listed companies.
</P>
<P>
The report said, however, the stock exchange authority did not
take any measure to cool the overheated market because some of the
bourses' leaders themselves were engaged in such fraudulent
activities.
</P>
<P>
The accused include the chief of the Dhaka Stock Exchange (DSE)
Imtiaz Hossain and former DSE chairman and present councilor
Khurshid Alam.
</P>
<P>
Starting from December last year, the DSE share price index
slid to a low of 1070 points at the end of a bearish trend. It
rallied back this week and the index Wednesday was slightly up
ending at 1225.49 points.
</P>
<P>
According to the DSE sources, trading at the DSE is likely to
be held as usual today although cases were filed against some of
the important dealers and brokers of the bourse.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, SEC Chairman Haroonur Rashid Wednesday said that the
commission would seek maximum punishment for those responsible for
the happenings in the stock market.
</P>
<P>
The government's action against the companies and brokers
responsible for the fraudulent acts would restore the confidence
of investors and help maintain normal trend and stability in the
share market, he hoped. 
</P>
</TEXT>
