<HEADLINE> San Miguel Internationalizes Soft Drinks Interests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 3 (Xinhua) -- San Miguel Corporation of the
Philippines announced here today that it has reached an agreement
in principle to combine its soft drinks interests with those of
Coca-Cola Amatil Ltd. (CCA) of Australia in a transaction valued
at about 2.7 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
"This move offers San Miguel a magnificent opportunity to
advance its internationalization program," said Andres Soriano,
chairman and chief executive officer of San Miguel, at a press
conference here today.
</P>
<P>
"In one dynamic step, we are able to expand the horizon of our
soft drink business from the Philippine domestic market to the
international arena through an anchor bottler spanning three
continents. This will also open up career opportunities for our
people," he said.
</P>
<P>
Soriano said that his company will combine its 70 percent-owned
subsidiary, Coca-Cola Bottlers Philippines, Inc (CCBPI), with CCA,
one of the Coca-Cola Company's largest anchor bottlers outside the
United States, and become its second largest shareholder with a
shareholding of 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Coca-Cola Company, which owns 30 percent of CCBPI, will
remain CCA's largest shareholder at 33 percent, he said.
</P>
<P>
Under the terms of the proposed transaction, Soriano said, CCA
will issue 293 million ordinary shares worth about 2.7 billion
dollars based on an average of CCA's share price for the month of
March. San Miguel will receive shares worth about 1.9 billion
dollars, he said.
</P>
<P>
San Miguel is the Philippines' largest beverage, food and
packing company with consolidated net sales of 3.2 billion dollars
and net income of 232 million dollars in 1996.  
</P>
</TEXT>
