<HEADLINE> China Exports Ostriches to DPRK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 3 (Xinhua)-- Twenty-one African ostriches were
exported by Beijing recently to the Democratic People's Republic
of Korea (DPRK), where they will be bred.
</P>
<P>
The ostriches came from the Shoujia Ostrich Breeding Farm in
Shunyi, a suburb of the Chinese capital, which will be responsible
for technical training of the DPRK developers.
</P>
<P>
The ostrich, a native of Africa, is a cash crop because the
price of the meat is 10 times that of beef, and the skin can sell
for more than 1,000 US dollars apiece, because of its softness and
beauty.
</P>
<P>
Other reasons for ostriches' world-wide popularity among
livestock raisers are the thickness of the meat, the long
life-span, and the rapid breeding.
</P>
<P>
Ostrich-breeding for commercial purposes in China began in the
late 1980s and has developed quickly since then. There are
currently more than 400 ostrich-raising companies in 21 provinces,
municipalities, and autonomous regions that are raising around
60,000 birds in all. In the Shoujia Ostrich Breeding Farm, the
biggest of its kind in north China, there will be over 1500
ostriches by the end of this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
