<HEADLINE> Strong Earthquakes Rock Japan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April (Xinhua) -- Two separate strong earthquakes shook
three of Japan's four main islands early thursday and at least
four people were injured in the stronger one, Japan's
Meteorological Agency said.
</P>
<P>
The first earthquake, measuring 5.5 on the open-ended Richter
scale, occurred at 4:33 a.m. (1933 GMT Wednesday) in Kagoshima
prefecture on Japan's southernmost main island of Kyushu, the
agency said.
</P>
<P>
The quake, which was centered about 10 kilometers deep in the
prefecture's Satsuma region, was also felt in the neighboring
Miyazaki and Kumamoto prefectures.
</P>
<P>
The tremor injured at least four people and caused landslides
at 14 locations, damaged roads at three locations and five
buildings in Kagoshima Prefecture, local authorities said.
</P>
<P>
The second quake, measuring 5.1 on the Richter scale, came at
6:47 a.m. (2147 GMT Wednesday). It jolted Ehime Prefecture on
Shikoku Island, the smallest of Japan's four main islands, Oita
Prefecture on Kyushu as well as several locations in the Chugoku
region on the biggest main island of Honshu.
</P>
<P>
There were no immediate reports of injuries or damages from the
second quake, police said.
</P>
<P>
Japan, one of the world's most earthquake-prone countries, has
experienced moderate to strong tremors in recent weeks on the Izu
Peninsula, southwest of Tokyo, in Aichi Prefecture and neighboring
prefectures in central Japan, and on the southern Kyushu Island.
</P>
</TEXT>
