<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Foreigners Seek Property Bargains in Thailand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Foreign investors are hunting for
bargains in Thailand's slumping property market.
</P>
<P>
Thailand has been facing a property depression for about three
years now, and cash-strapped Thai developers are offering
discounts for their properties.
</P>
<P>
Thai developers lack cash flow because they cannot sell units
as a result of oversupply.
</P>
<P>
Developers are also facing difficulty securing more loans to
complete construction because of the Bank of Thailand's credit
squeeze on the property sector.
</P>
<P>
The depressed property sector has become a burden to the
country's commercial banks and finance firms, as developers are
unable to repay their loans.
</P>
<P>
Average property prices in Thailand are now 20 percent to 30
percent below the levels seen at the peak of the property boom
four or five years ago, according to an executive of real-estate
consultants Colliers Jardine.
</P>
<P>
Normally, property investors expect returns of about 12
percent. But in Thailand a more realistic rate would now be 7
percent to 8 percent for the office, residential and retail
sectors.
</P>
<P>
Foreign investors, in particular Singaporeans and Malaysians,
consider now a good time to enter Thailand's property market.
</P>
<P>
Most foreign investors realize the current situation and are
investing for the long term, after they calculate the capital
gains, added value from their properties and risk and returns on
purchases.
</P>
<P>
The most attractive area for foreigners is serviced apartments,
for which demand is outpacing supply. Offshore investors will buy
Thai properties through joint ventures with Thai partners.
</P>
<P>
The attractiveness of serviced apartments is due to the
increase in long-term demand for accommodations for foreign
executives who work in Thailand. And the flow of more foreign
investment to Thailand means that more such residential units are
needed.
</P>
<P>
There are two types of potential investors: individuals who
will buy one to five units, and others who want to buy whole
buildings.
</P>
<P>
Institutional investors and large listed firms from Singapore
and Malaysia are looking for office spaces in Bangkok.
</P>
<P>
The average office vacancy rate is 18 percent in the central
business district and 24 percent in the suburbs.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970403.0203 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Asian Nations Agree on Sub-Regional Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Four South Asian countries
agreed to form an expert group to further study the priorities of
the proposed sub-regional cooperation at the conclusion of a
one-day foreign secretary level meeting held here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Foreign secretaries of Bangladesh, Bhutan, India and Nepal held
preliminary discussions on the projects which would be further
studied later on the costs and benefits, according to the Nepali
Foreign Ministry.
</P>
<P>
The areas of cooperation between the four countries would be
determined in line with the study report expected to come out
after the expert group's meeting in July this year, Nepali Foreign
Secretary Kumar Prasad Gyawali told a press conference on
Wednesday evening.
</P>
<P>
Foreign secretaries of the four countries said the sub-regional
cooperation, known as the South Asian Growth Quadrangle, would not
overshadow the cooperation under the seven-nation South Asian
Association for Regional Cooperation (SAARC) and expressed their
respective governments' commitment to SAARC activities.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh Foreign Secretary Farooq said the concept of the
four-nation sub-regional cooperation is in pursuit of SAARC policy
under which two or more SAARC countries can work together for
mutual interests.
</P>
<P>
The concept of sub-regional cooperation was raised by Nepali
Foreign Minister Prakash Chandra Lohani in New Delhi at a meeting
of SAARC council of ministers last December.
</P>
<P>
Lohani proposed that the four South Asian countries in the
sub-region enhance their cooperation in areas like hydro-power,
transport, trade, transit, tourism and communications.  
</P>
</TEXT>
