<HEADLINE> Price Growth Slows in Vietnam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Prices of goods and services in
Vietnam grew 2.1 percent in the first quarter of this year, the
lowest growth rate for many years, Vietnam's Deputy Prime Minister
Phan Van Khai said here today.
</P>
<P>
But he warned that although the country's social and economic
development continued improving in the first few months of the
year, signs of a slowdown were being seen in manufacturing and
business activities in some sectors, particularly the processing
industry.
</P>
<P>
Khai was speaking at today's opening of the 11th and final
session of the country's Ninth National Assembly (parliament) to
review the country's socio-economic development, defense, security
and external relations.
</P>
<P>
In his report, Khai said that the country had managed to
overcome the consequences of last year's floods and storms.
</P>
<P>
Farmers in the Mekong River delta provinces have started
harvesting the winter-spring rice crop which is expected to be a
bumper one.
</P>
<P>
He said industrial output grew 14 percent in the first quarter
of this year compared with the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Exports rose 22.5 percent to 1.79 billion U.S. dollars,
with exports of foreign invested enterprises soaring 83.9 percent
to 160 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Imports in the past three months rose a more modest 10.7
percent to 2.72 billion U.S. dollars over the same period in 1996.
</P>
<P>
But Khai warned that the trade deficit was rising quickly and
had already exceeded the "safety level."
</P>
<P>
He said the slow disbursement of investment funds for
capital construction from both the state budget and foreign loans
delayed several development projects.
</P>
<P>
Reforms of the state apparatus in general and of the
administrative and state-owned economic sectors in particular were
also slow, Khai added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
