<HEADLINE> Argentina Marks Veterans' Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Argentine President Carlos
Menem today took part in a ceremony of the Veterans' Day this
morning to commemorate the 15th anniversary of Argentina's landing
on the Malvinas (Falkland) Islands.
</P>
<P>
The ceremony was held at a monument built in memory of those
who died on the Malvinas Islands.
</P>
<P>
During the ceremony, President Menem, accompanied by Defense
Minister Jorge Dominguez and the commanders of the armed forces,
laid a wreath at the monument.
</P>
<P>
In his speech, Admiral Jorge Enrico, chief of the joint chiefs
of staff, said that those who sacrificed their lives for the
country during the Malvinas (Falkland) war in 1982 did not die in
vain.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that one day "the blue and white flag
will again flutter over the Malvina Islands."
</P>
<P>
Before this ceremony, there was a mass offered in memory of
those who died during the Malvinas (Falkland) War.
</P>
<P>
Before the mass, Defense Minister Jorge Dominguez reaffirmed
the government's confidence that Argentina will be able to
exercise its sovereignty over the Malvinas (Falkland).
</P>
<P>
Last night, the Federation of Argentine Veterans paid their
tributes including a guard of honor in front of the flag.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Guido di Tella sent 17,000 letters to the
veterans who fought in the war to acknowledge their participation
and to ask them to remain optimistic about recovering the islands.
</P>
<P>
On April 2, 1982, Argentina's armed forces landed on the
Malvinas (Falkland) Islands in an attempt to regain its
sovereignty over the archipelago occupied by Britain since
1833. Argentine forces were defeated in the war. 
</P>
</TEXT>
