<HEADLINE> Ukraine, China Seek Close Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Ukraine will hold to the One-China
policy and will not set up official links with Taiwan, Ukrainian
President Leonid Kuchma said here today.
</P>
<P>
Meeting with visiting Chinese Vice Premier Wu Bangguo,
Kuchma said he was satisfied with the growing relations between
Ukraine and China.
</P>
<P>
Ukraine is willing to develop broader cooperation with China,
which boasts boundless potential, and hopes that China will
increase investment in Ukraine, said he.
</P>
<P>
The president also expressed Ukraine's interest in China's
Three Gorges project, saying that Wu's visit will further promote
the development of the relations between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Speaking highly of Kuchma's contribution to the friendly
cooperation between the two countries, Wu said Sino-Ukrainian ties
have seen steady and smooth development since the two countries
established diplomatic relations in 1991.
</P>
<P>
China appreciated Ukraine's commitment concerning China's
internal issues like Taiwan and Tibet, and mutual support and
cooperation are the major characteristics of the bilateral
relations between China and Ukraine, he said.
</P>
<P>
"We share the same or similar views on important issues," said
Wu, who arrived here Sunday for a three-day visit.
</P>
<P>
China attaches great importance to developing bilateral
relationship with Ukraine, an important European country with
great potential. He said the promotion of the relationship is in
the interest of two countries, he said.
</P>
<P>
China will as usual support Ukrainian sovereignty, independence
and territorial integrity, added the Chinese vice premier.
</P>
<P>
Earlier today, Wu met Prime Minister Pavel Lazarenko.
</P>
<P>
Ukraine is the first leg of Wu's European tour, which will take
him to Belarus, the Czech Republic, Finland and Switzerland. 
</P>
</TEXT>
