<DOCNO> XIE19970403.0215 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand Encourages Merger of Finance Firms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 3 (Xinhua) -- The Bank of Thailand has
introduced a package of incentives for finance companies to merge
and increase the stability and competitiveness of the financial
sector.
</P>
<P>
Firms interested in merging can apply to the central bank
immediately, according to a senior official of the bank today.
</P>
<P>
The incentives include eligibility for new retail banking
operations, such as the ability to accept passbook savings
deposits and run foreign exchange operations, as well as
permission to expand branch networks.
</P>
<P>
To qualify, the group must have a lead firm composed of one to
three companies with a combined net capital of 3 billion baht (120
million US dollars) and net assets of 30 billion baht (1.2 billion
dollars).
</P>
<P>
The central bank also announced Wednesday that finance
companies that merge and need to rebuild their capital through
foreign participation above the 25 percent shareholding limit will
be favorably considered on a case-by-case basis.
</P>
<P>
Policy makers believe that increased financial stability will
not only boost investor interest and spur stock prices, but also
ease depositor worries, leading to reduced costs.
</P>
<P>
Central bank governor Rerngchai Marakanond said firms which
decline to merge or boost capital would face tighter restrictions
in the future.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said the new move amounts to a handout of incentives
to more than 90 finance companies generally considered
second-class financial institutions due to the narrower scope of
their financial services compared with commercial banks. The
finance companies, which are barred from providing checking
account services, trade financing and foreign exchange, are
suffering bad debts in loan portfolios incurred from ventures into
high-risk businesses.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that the Finance Ministry is also examining
other measures which would encourage financial institutions to
shift away from relying on short-term foreign capital to fund
domestic activities, which can lead to problems of maturity
mismatches.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
