<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vienna Philharmonic Orchestra Director Resigns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, April 2 (Xinhua) -- The director of the Vienna
Philharmonic Orchestra, Professor Werner Resel, resigned tonight,
leaving the world-famous orchestra "headless".
</P>
<P>
Resel refused to elaborate on why, except to say it was for
personal reasons.
</P>
<P>
A cellist himself, Resel had held the post since 1987. He
became a member of the National Opera Theatre of Austria in 1959.
</P>
<P>
The Vienna Philharmonic Orchestra, founded in 1842 and famous
for its annual New Year's concert, is a private association and
its members play at the publicly-funded Vienna State Opera.
</P>
<P>
It was an all-male orchestra until early this year when, under
heavy pressure from the government and vehement attacks from
feminist groups, it began to admit female members.
</P>
<P>
Resel had been reluctant to let in women members to the
orchestra. His aide, Deputy Director Clemens Hellsberg, will take
care of the orchestra's business until a new director is elected.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970403.0223 </DOCNO>
