<DOCNO> XIE19970403.0224 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italian Troops Won't Avoid Albania South </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Italian Foreign Minister Lamberto
Dini today denied reports that Italy will avoid sending troops to
rebel-held southern Albania because of anti-Italian sentiment
following the sinking of a refugee boat.
</P>
<P>
He said details of the deployment of the multinational
protection force (MPF) were yet to be decided.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a joint press conference with the Organization of
Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE) envoy to Albania, former
Austrian Chancellor Franz Vranitsky, Dini said "signals" here on
Tuesday indicated that "Italian troops would be welcomed to the
south."
</P>
<P>
Anti-Italy sentiment reportly flared in the south after an
Albanian refugee boat collided with an Italian navy ship and sank
in the Adriatic Sea on Friday night. There are four dead and 83
people missing.
</P>
<P>
There have been expressions of strong resentment against Italy
especially in the southern port of Vlore, from where the ill-fated
boat left. People have threatened to shoot any Italian troops who
come as part of the force.
</P>
<P>
However, a spokesman for the rebel salvation committee in Vlore
said today it was keen for Italy to send troops and they would run
no risks.
</P>
<P>
Dini said decisions on deployment of the 5,000-strong MPF will
be made later today at the meeting of 70 military representatives
and diplomats from 10 countries ready to contribute troops.
</P>
<P>
Italy is expected to provide 2,000 to 2,500 troops, France
1,000, Greece 700, Spain 500, Turkey 500 and Romania 400.
</P>
<P>
The troops will be headed by 57-year-old Italian General
Luciano Forlani, at present the commander of the third armored
corps based in Milan.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile in Tirana, the Albanian government renewed its call
for the force to be sent as soon as possible, and in any event no
later than April 12.
</P>
<P>
Facing criticism from opposition parties that the MPF will put
Italian soldiers in danger, Italian Defense Minister, Beniamino
Andreatta, replied today that Italian servicemen would only be
used on logistical duties in areas that were completely calm.
</P>
<P>
He said he did not envisage the force undertaking police
operations, but simply securing access to the troubled Balkan
country and defending supply routes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970403.0225 </DOCNO>
