<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More MNLF Members to Join MILF Rebels in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Some 10,000 members of the Moro
National Liberation Front (MNLF) have defected to another rebel
group, the Moro Islamic Liberation Front (MILF) since the MNLF
singed a peace agreement with the Philippine government last
September.
</P>
<P>
Business World, a local newspaper, reported today that some
7,000 more MNLF members are expected to follow their disillusioned
comrades soon. However, the reports need to be confirmed by the
MNLF or the Philippine government.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted MILF vice-chairman for political affairs
Ghadzali Jaafar as saying that many members of the MNLF are
discouraged because the economic development in Mindanao promised
by the government has yet to be realized.
</P>
<P>
According to the MILF, many MNLF members are turning to the
MILF because they "do not believe" that the peace agreement is the
real solution to the problems of the Moro people.
</P>
<P>
In its peace talks, the MILF has repeatedly asked the
government to consider giving the Moro people an independent state
in Mindanao. The MNLF also made the same demand, but dropped it
later to reach a peace agreement with the government.
</P>
<P>
As a result, an estimated 10,000 members of the MNLF from all
over Mindanao have changed sides and transferred to the MILF, the
newspaper said, adding that 7,000 more have informally indicated
their intention to cross over to the MILF.
</P>
<P>
Since the MNLF has made peace with the government, the MILF
claimed that it is now the biggest rebel group with 350,000 troops
in Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
Local analysts said if the reports are confirmed, it would be a
great setback to the peace process in the southern Philippines.
</P>
<P>
Philippine President Fidel Ramos was reportedly worried over
the defection and have instructed all government agencies to
expedite other programs to attend to the needs of the MNLF.
</P>
<P>
The MILF is a breakaway faction of the MNLF. The government is
now pursuing low-level talks with it, but the talks were sometimes
stalled by sporadic fighting between the two sides.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
