<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Number of Collectors In China on Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, April 3 (Xinhua) -- North China's Tianjin
municipality, which is said to have 400,000 collectors, has come
to have one of the largest collections of collectors in China.
</P>
<P>
As could be seen in a recent exhibition, the objects of their
affection include an exotic array of cigarette packages, post
cards, cards of scenic spots, porcelain, types of make-up used in
traditional operas, leather silhouettes, rare stones, coins,
rubbings, and foreign clocks and watches.
</P>
<P>
The most eye-catching exhibit was perhaps the 1.3 m-by-3.3 m
picture made of more than 20,000 rare fish bones that were
collected by an over 60-year-old local retiree, Zhao Gang.
</P>
<P>
The fish bones were used to make two large dragons, four small
dragons, and a floral ball, and 12 Chinese characters which mean
"unity, reunification", "descendants of heavenly dragon' and "the
motherland's reunification".
</P>
<P>
Some 100 blue and white porcelain pots with designs made by
famous painters and calligraphers were on display, as part of 40
types of exhibits from 46 local collectors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
