<BODY>
<HEADLINE> First Group of Scholars Sent Abroad by Reformed System Return </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Chinese scholars who were sent
abroad for further training returned home, showing the
effectiveness of the reformed policy.
</P>
<P>
Seven of 10 scholars who finished their studies abroad kept
their promise by returning home on schedule, with another two
people ready to return with booked air tickets in hands, said an
official from the China Scholarship Council (CSC), a non-profit
institution established last June to take over the State Education
Commission's tasks of handling affairs related to overseas studies.
</P>
<P>
China began to reform its way of sending scholars abroad for
academic research and exchanges two years ago. Northeast China's
Jilin and east China's Jiangsu provinces took the lead in
reforming the old method in an experimental way.
</P>
<P>
The reform, introduced nationwide one year later, offers
opportunity to those who want to study abroad with the state
financial support. They can submit a personal application and go
through a selection procedure by a panel of relevant experts.
</P>
<P>
If selected, they must sign an agreement with the government to
pledge to return home after completing their overseas studies.
</P>
<P>
The two provinces selected 86 people to study abroad. And the
10 people of them are the first group to return as scheduled.
</P>
<P>
The CSC official said that those who break the agreement have
an extra period of two months to make a yes-or-no decision. If
they choose not to come back, the CSC will deal with the matter
according to the agreement. The earnest money they deposit in a
bank will be fined and their guarantors will be investigated and
affixed responsibility.
</P>
<P>
He said CSC is taking management of overseas scholars as a
major task this year as scholars abroad are lining up to come back
home.
</P>
<P>
The CSC has granted about 1,500 applicants with further
training or research opportunities abroad last year. It is now
open for applications for another 1,500 opportunities. This year's
selection work is expected to be completed in late August.
</P>
<P>
About 270,000 Chinese have gone abroad for advanced training
since 1978 when late Chinese leader Deng Xiaoping advocated
sending more people overseas to study. Over 120,000 of them were
sponsored by the State or their work units, with the remainder
self-supporting.
</P>
<P>
Some 90,000 of these people have completed their overseas study
and returned.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
