<HEADLINE> Venezuela Signs Oil Cooperation Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, April 2 (Xinhua) -- The Venezuelan National Congress
approved today the signing of a cooperation agreement between a
Venezuelan oil company and three United States companies involving
an investment of about 3.5 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, for the production, transport and refining of
extra heavy crude oil, was signed by Corpoven, a subsidiary of
Petroleos de Venezuela.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. companies are Atlantic Richfield Co. (ARCO), Texaco
Inc. and the Philips Petroleum Company.
</P>
<P>
The four companies will produce improved oil and other products
from the refining process in the Hamaca area of the Orinoco oil
fields.
</P>
<P>
The cooperation aims to develop reserves of crude oil deposits
in an economic way, and take advantage of the apparent growing
demand for crude oil in the next few years.
</P>
<P>
Corpoven says about 3.5 billion dollars will be invested in
camp facilities, drilling, transportation and the improvement of
crude oil. Daily production will be 195,000 barrels of extra heavy
oil.
</P>
<P>
The product will be piped to the refining plant to be installed
in a complex in the northern part of the Anzoategui state.
</P>
<P>
The three U.S. oil companies will own 70 percent share of the
stocks and Corpoven 30 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
