<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Trade Increases Between Chinese Hainan And Taiwan Islands </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, April 3 (Xinhua) -- The volume of trade between south
China's Hainan Province and Taiwan last year grew 37.5 percent
over 1995, as a result of increasing cooperation in the
agricultural sector.
</P>
<P>
Farm produce and sideline products accounted for the majority
of Hainan's exports to Taiwan. According to customs statistics,
the trade volume registered 33.99 million US dollars last year,
14.5 million in imports and 19.49 million in exports.
</P>
<P>
The year's growth was 37.5 percent for the total trade volume,
35.3 percent for imports, and 38.4 percent for exports, much
higher than overall growth of Hainan's trade in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Some 57 percent of the export volume, 11.14 million US dollars
worth, was in aquatic products, vegetables and tea, most from
Taiwan-backed agricultural projects.
</P>
<P>
And 46 percent of the imports were machinery and electric
machinery, most of which were imported by Taiwan-backed businesses
as a part of their investment.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that the actual trade volume between Hainan and
Taiwan is much larger than the official figures, because many
exports to Hong Kong ultimately go to Taiwan. They predict future
increases in trade because of preferential policies in tariffs and
taxes Hainan has as a special economic zone, and expanding
Taiwanese investment in Hainan and Hainan's potential in
processing with its rich natural resources and low land and labor
costs.
</P>
<P>
They say that direct sea and air links should be established
between Hainan and Taiwan to fuel development.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
