<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Promotes Inter-region Economic Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai, China's economic and
financial center, is making an effort to promote inter-regional
cooperation and has spent 1.82 billion yuan on 100 inter-regional
cooperation projects.
</P>
<P>
These resulted in an increase of annual production capacity of
2.35 million bikes, 550,000 TV sets, 80,000 tons of detergent and
53 million batteries.
</P>
<P>
The city invested in 20 automobile projects and developed 66
parts and component enterprises along the Yangtze River. A
takeover of the Haikou Tire Co. last year allowed Shanghai Tire
Co., one of the country's major tire producers, to increase
revenues from 3.5 billion yuan to more than 10 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
According to one local official, the scope of cooperation was
widened last year from the industrial and commercial sector to
finance, scientific research, agriculture, tourism and education.
</P>
<P>
The Shanghai Jinjiang Hotel Management Group used its expertise
in 34 hotels and eight other properties across the country.
</P>
<P>
Profit is not the only goal of the cooperation. Last year the
city worked with Yunnan in poverty relief in the economically
backward province in southwest China. Shanghai has signed
contracts and letters of intent with Yunnan worth 2.5 billion yuan
in different fields, including industry, agriculture, and foreign
trade.
</P>
<P>
It has also spent 300 million yuan on Three Gorges Dam-related
projects.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai is also taking advantage of its unique status in
China's opening drive. Some 1,996 enterprises funded by investors
out of Shanghai settled in the city last year. The registered
capital of these ventures totalled 3.2 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Some 220 machine-building enterprises and financial
institutions across the country formed the China Pufa Corporation,
headquartered in Shanghai's Pudong New Area, with assets of more
than one billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
The First Auto Works, the country's largest automobile
manufacturer in northeast China's Jilin Province, has spent 150
million yuan on a plant capable of producing 6,000 Red Flag
mid-luxury sedans in Nanhui County, one of Shanghai's suburban
counties. The auto group signed another 12 letters of intent for
an investment of 250 million yuan with the county. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
