<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Beats Sweden in Soccer Friendly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 2 (Xinhua) -- A questionable foul led to the only
score by Youri Djorkaeff helped France for a unconvincing 1-0 win
over Sweden in a soccer friendly here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
There were few opportunities for either team in the first
half. Although France had the majority of play on the Swedish
side of the field, French goalie Fabien Barthez made the two major
stops of the first half, getting in front of two headed shots by
Swedes.
</P>
<P>
Just when it would appear to be a scoreless first half, France
scored.
</P>
<P>
In the 44th minute, Djorkaeff evaded the defense and was
approached by Thomas Ravelli, the Swedish goalie, in the penalty
area.
</P>
<P>
Although TV replays showed Djorkaeff making a late fall with
Ravelli not touching him, the Belgian referee, Marnix Sandra,
awarded Djorkaeff a penalty which he converted for his 14th
international goal for France.
</P>
<P>
In the second half Christophe Dugarry made Ravelli dive to stop
a shot in the 55th minute. Franck Gava, who came into the game a
little after, made Ravelli work with a direct shot on goal minutes
later.
</P>
<P>
The rest of the half was on equal terms with neither goalie
being really threatened.
</P>
<P>
The last time Sweden beat France was in 1969. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
