<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brazil, Argentina Reach Trade Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Brazil and Argentina today
reached an agreement which could end the trade dispute between the
two countries generated by Brazil's import restrictions.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was signed by Brazilian Finance Minister Pedro
Malan and visiting Argentine Economy Minister Roque Fernandez, who
arrived here today for the talks of the agreement.
</P>
<P>
The move is believed to benefit only Argentina, Paraguay and
Uruguay, Brazil's three parters in the Southern Common
Market (Mercosur).
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, the imports made by any one of the
Mercosur partners will not have to be paid in cash after clearing
customs. payment must be guaranteed by the central banks of each
country through reciprocal credit agreements which allow the
signatory countries having a "current account" to pay the
difference at the end of each four-month period.
</P>
<P>
Last week, the Brazilian government announced restrictions on
the financing of imports in order to reduce its trade
deficit. Under the restrictions, importers would have to pay for
all of imported goods immediately.
</P>
<P>
The measure would affect 65 percent of the Brazilian imports
and would also harm the interests of Argentina, uruguay and
paraguay.
</P>
<P>
The governments of Argentina, Uruguay and Paraguay expressed
their strong opposition to the Brazilian decision.
</P>
<P>
Chile and Bolivia, both associate members of the trade bloc, are
expected to have talks with Brazil on the same issue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
