<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hungary Refuses to Join Multinational Force to Albania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUDAPEST, April 2 (Xinhua) -- The Hungarian government has
refused to send troops to join the U.N.-approved multinational
force to protect relief operations and help restore order in
crisis-hit Albania.
</P>
<P>
Hungarian Prime Minister Gyula Horn said that after discussions
with President Arpad Goncz and all political parties, his
government turned down a request from Italy for 250 servicemen to
join the Italian-led multinational force.
</P>
<P>
He said it would create a bad precedent for the international
community to go in to solve a country's internal conflicts.
</P>
<P>
In contrast to U.N military intervention, he said, the
multinational force could not guarantee its own security in
lawless Albania and so it was pointless risking Hungarian
servicemen's lives there.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council last Friday authorized the dispatch
of a 2,500-strong Italian-led multinational force for three months
to protect relief operations and help the return to stability and
order in Albania.
</P>
<P>
Albania has repeatedly asked for foreign military assistance
since massive protests, sparked by the collapse of pyramid savings
schemes, turned into armed violence last month. More than 150
people have been killed in the unrest. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
