<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines, Switzerland Eyeing Tax Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 3 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine and Swiss
governments are negotiating for a bilateral tax treaty to
eliminate double taxation and encourage investments between the
two countries.
</P>
<P>
Swiss Public Economic Minister Jean Pascal Delamuraz, head of a
trade delegation which just ends a three-day visit to the country,
said the double taxation appeared to hinder the flow of Swiss
investments into the Philippines, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
He said that profits generated from investments should be taxed
only once, stressing that the proposed tax deal would help attract
investments and level the playing field for Swiss investors.
</P>
<P>
Switzerland now has existing double taxation agreements with
most countries in the Southeast Asian region.
</P>
<P>
Andres Leuenberger, president of the Swiss Federation of
Commerce and Industry, added that many Swiss firms were eyeing
investments in the Philippines, particularly in infrastructure and
engineering projects under the build-operate-transfer
arrangements.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
