<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Horner Beaten in British Squash Open </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Suzanne Horner, sixth seed at the
British Open, was unexpectedly crashed out of the tournament in
Cardiff on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Horner was beaten by England international Linda Charman 9-3,
9-3, 8-10, 5-9, 9-1 but she looked as though she was digging
herself out of trouble after she had saved two match points in
the third game.
</P>
<P>
However she turned her left ankle in the second game and by the
fifth it was beginning to slow her down.
</P>
<P>
Charman took advantage cleverly, mixing volley drops with
sudden fierce drives in chilly conditions which slowed the ball
and required players to chase further to reach it.
</P>
<P>
At the end Horner could only limp off the court and afterwards
needed to have the ankle treated and strapped before she could
walk properly.
</P>
<P>
Charman next plays the fourth-seeded British national champion
Sue Wright, who did complete a recovery from two games down in a
controversial match against her compatriot Rebecca Macree at 7-9,
3-9, 9-4, 9-6, 9-4.
</P>
<P>
Later the world number two from Australia Rodney Eyles came
through for a men's quarter-final with the world's most
dangerously improved player, the sixth-seeded Canadian Jonathan
Power.
</P>
<P>
Eyles had to work hard over four games to get past Mark
Chaloner and Power was devastating in winning 15-3, 15-2, 15-12
against Julien Bonetat.
</P>
<P>
Later Eyles compatriot, the former British Open finalist Brett
Martin, reached the quarter-finals with a four-game win over the
British national champion Mark Cairns who put up a remarkably good
performance only two weeks after having an operation for a
detached retina.
</P>
<P>
Martin meets the world number three from Scotland, Peter Nicol,
who really seems to have broken his British Open hoodoo after
four years of trying.
</P>
<P>
Nicol won 15-5, 10-15, 15-8, 15-12 against another Aussie
Anthony Hill. 
</P>
</TEXT>
