<HEADLINE> International Assistance Improves Chinese Women, Children's Health </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Funds from the United Nations and
the World Health Organization have helped improve the health of
women and children in northwest China's Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous
Region.
</P>
<P>
Over the past six years, the region has had various health
projects sponsored by the UN Children's Fund, the UN Population
Fund, and the World Health Organization.
</P>
<P>
Involving 1.26 million US dollars, the projects have benefited
some 3.6 million people in seven prefectures and sixteen counties.
</P>
<P>
Local governments at all levels spent 14.4 million yuan (about
1.7 million US dollars) during the six-year period to supplement
the foreign aid, six million yuan (about 700,000 US dollars) more
than the previously-promised amount.
</P>
<P>
A five-year project, jointly sponsored by the UN Children's
Fund and the Chinese government, was launched recently, which will
receive 700,000 US dollars from the Children's Fund and ten
million yuan (about 1.2 million US dollars) from local governments.
</P>
<P>
The project is intended to improve medical services at the
grass-roots level for women and children, increasing the number of
medical personnel, and improving their skills.
</P>
<P>
The projects will benefit 23 counties and cities in 11
prefectures, and provide services for 5.27 million people, or
nearly 32 percent of the region's total population. 
</P>
</TEXT>
