<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Hopes Order to Be Restored in Zaire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 2 (Xinhua) -- The United States today
expressed the hope that Zaire's new prime minister would negotiate
an end to the conflict inside the war-torn central African
country.
</P>
<P>
Zairian President Mobutu Sese Seko today formally approved the
appointment of Etienne Tshisekedi as prime minister to steer Zaire
through the civil war.
</P>
<P>
U.S. State Department spokesman Nicholas Burns said, "The first
order of business for the new Zairian government will be to
negotiate an end to the conflict inside Zaire and to prepare for
arrangements for a political transition in Zaire."
</P>
<P>
Burns said the United States was concerned about the dire
situation of the refugees in eastern Zaire as they are in "a very
weakened state."
</P>
<P>
He called on Zaire's rebel leader Laurent Kabila to cooperate
with a U.N. plan to repatriate thousands of Rwandan refugees still
trapped in eastern Zaire.
</P>
<P>
"This is a very serious situation," he said. "There have been
good promises from Mr. Kabila and his forces, but they have not
come through with the action necessary to give the United Nations
access to the refugees, and some of those refugees have perished."
</P>
<P>
The repatriation plan requires Kabila's consent to allow relief
workers to get through the rebel-controlled city of Kisangani to
reach some 80,000 refugees situated some 16 to 25 miles south of
the city, Burns said. And to airlift the refugees needs Kabila's
permission.
</P>
<P>
"We call for urgent approval by him (Kabila), and consent of
this UNHCR (United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees)
repatriation plan and the assistance operations so that further
deaths and suffering can be prevented and rapid and safe
repatriation of the refugees can begin," Burns said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
