<HEADLINE> Port at Sino-Russian Border Busy Handling Foreign Trade Goods </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Manzhouli, a land port of entry on
the Sino-Russian border, handled over seven million tons of import
and export goods in 1996, 60 percent of the total handled by land
ports across China.
</P>
<P>
The value of the goods passing through Manzhouli reached 230
million US dollars, a rise of 48 percent over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Manzhouli in the Inner Mongolian Autonomous Region is where a
trunk railway linking Beijing with Moscow meets.
</P>
<P>
In order to cope with growing foreign trade, great efforts have
been made by the city to improve relevant conditions, city
officials said.
</P>
<P>
The past few years have seen the completion of a number of
infrastructure projects including a Sino-Russian border trade
zone, an international telecommunications building, renovation of
railway stations, new highways, an airport, and the
computerization of customs procedures.
</P>
<P>
As a result of the improved environment, the city was cited as
a national-level model port of entry in the 1995-96 period.
</P>
<P>
The city has also become a magnet for overseas investment,
having already drawing investors from Singapore, the Republic of
Korea, Taiwan, and Hongkong to launch 27 new projects with a total
of 120 million yuan in investment.
</P>
<P>
Investors from all over the country have set up over
300 enterprises and companies in this border city. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
