<HEADLINE> US Dollar Rebounds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, April 2 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. dollar rose sharply in
New York today after a Bank of Japan survey suggested interest
rates there will remain low.
</P>
<P>
The rebound erased most of the dollar's losses from the day
before, when rumors about unexpectedly strong results from the
so-called Tankan survey and fears over Rubin's upcoming Japan trip
helped push the dollar to a three-week low vs. the yen, a six-week
low vs. the mark and a 10-week low vs. the pound.
</P>
<P>
The dollar settled at 123.25 yen, up from 121.76 yen Tuesday.
The dollar cost 1.6765 marks, up from 1.6656. The pound cost
1.6431 U.S. dollars, down from 1.6528 U.S. dollars. The dollar
ended higher against most other currencies.
</P>
<P>
Other late dollar rates in New York compared with Tuesday:
1.4443 Swiss francs, up from 1.4415; 5.6430 French francs, up from
5.6075; 1,660.00 Italian lire, down from 1,663.00; 1.3860 Canadian
dollars, down from 1.3884. 
</P>
</TEXT>
