<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Low-Fat Diet Cuts Breast-Cancer Risk </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Canadian researchers have the first
proof that women who shift to a low-fat diet can greatly reduce a
major risk factor for breast cancer.
</P>
<P>
Women who trimmed the amount of calories they consume from fat
by about a third had a significant reduction in the amount of
dense tissue in their breasts over two years, according to the
study reported today in the Journal of the National Cancer
Institute.
</P>
<P>
Women whose breasts include more than 50 percent dense tissue
are up to five times as likely to develop cancer as those who have
little or no dense tissue.
</P>
<P>
In the study, half of the group of 818 women worked with
nutritionists to reduce the fat in their diets to an average of 21
percent. The difference was made up by adding carbohydrates.
</P>
<P>
The others in the study were given nutrition counseling but did
not change their diets, which averaged 32 percent fat. Many
Canadians get more than 35 percent of their calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
Over two years, the low-fat group experienced an average
6-percent decrease in the amount of dense breast tissue. Those who
did not restrict fat had a decrease of 2 percent, a reduction that
occurs normally as women age.
</P>
<P>
Menopause magnifies the effect. Women in the low-fat group who
also underwent menopause had a 20-percent reduction in the area of
dense breast tissue, compared with 10 percent in the group that
made no major diet changes.
</P>
<P>
Levels of estrogen in the body did not change significantly as
the fat level declined, and the researchers saw no significant
differences between the mammograms of women taking
hormone-replacement therapy and those of women who were not taking
hormones.
</P>
<P>
The findings are the first result from what will be a 10-year
study of breast health that will follow about 4,500 Canadian women
in Ontario and British Columbia provinces whose breasts include
more than 50 percent high-density tissue.
</P>
<P>
Only genetic mutations pose a higher breast-cancer risk, and
they are present in fewer than 10 percent of the population. Other
breast-cancer factors include age, early onset of menstruation,
late menopause, not having children of having a late first
pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
A woman's risk of developing breast cancer is about one in nine
over her lifetime. An estimated 18,400 new cases of breast cancer
will be diagnosed in Canada this year, and about 5,100 women will
die from it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
