<HEADLINE> NY Stocks Plunge Again on Interest-Rate Concerns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Investors sent stock prices on
Wall Street plunging again today on continuous concerns about
higher interest rates, knocking the Dow industrial average down
94.04 points, or 1.4 percent, to 6,517.01.
</P>
<P>
It fell as much as 111.41 points during the session, its first
time below 6,500 since early January.
</P>
<P>
The latest retreat means the Dow average has fallen 568.15
points, or 8 percent, from the all-time high of 7,085.16 reached
March 11. It still is up 1 percent for the year. A total of 364
points were lost since last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Dow has lost 363.69 points over the past four sessions and
fallen 8 percent from its all-time best close at 7,085.16, set less
than a month ago on March 11.
</P>
<P>
Declining issues outnumbered advancers by more than a 2-to-1
margin on the New York Stock Exchange, with NYSE volume totaling
478.13 million shares as against 507.06 million in the previous
session.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock list fell 9.53, or 1.25 percent,
to 750.11, and is now down more than 8 percent from its all-time
best close at 816.29, set February 18.
</P>
<P>
The Nasdaq composite index fell 16.47, or 1.3 percent, to
1,201.00, its lowest finish since September 17. The Nasdaq has now
retreated by 13.5 percent from its all-time high at 1,388.06, set
January 22.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE's composite index fell 4.43 to 395.37, and the American
Stock Exchange composite index fell 5.08 to 561.19. 
</P>
</TEXT>
