<HEADLINE> IMF Chief Praises Russia's Economic Achievements </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Michel Camdessus, managing
director of the International Monetary Fund (IMF), today praised
Russia's economic stabilization achieved in the last few years and
also highlighted three major problems in the economy.
</P>
<P>
In a speech prepared for delivery at the Moscow Institute of
International Affairs on April 2, Camdessus noted, "Inflation has
been cut... and the exchange rate has stabilized."
</P>
<P>
"Central planning has been abolished and... two-thirds of the
economy is now in private hands," he said. "Trade barriers have
been reduced, and the ruble trades freely and can be readily
converted into foreign exchange."
</P>
<P>
The IMF chief also pointed to three key problems concerning the
state that have to be addressed: growth, the non-payment of taxes,
and corruption.
</P>
<P>
He said that Russia's economic growth can be accelerated if the
government completes the institutional reforms on which a thriving
market economy depends. These include, he said, a simple and
transparent regulatory system, an effective legal and judicial
system that protects property rights, enforces contracts and helps
create an atmosphere of law, order and personal security as well
as a simple and broad-based tax system.
</P>
<P>
Camdessus stressed that the government should have the
"revenues to meet its obligations to workers, pensioners and all
who depend on government services. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
