<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Bankers' Fears on European Monetary Union Grow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 2 (Xinhua) -- The City of London financiers see
the European Monetary Union (EMU) as the fastest growing danger to
the European banking industry, outweighing rogue traders,
derivatives and unwise lending into emerging markets.
</P>
<P>
In a survey of 170 British bankers, lawyers, accountants and
regulators carried out by the Study of Financial Innovation, the
EMU, due to be launched in 1999, emerged as a serious danger
because of the political and economic strains it may cause.
</P>
<P>
The findings of the survey revealed that poor management was
the most frequently cited danger, though few respondents were as
harsh as a City lawyer who said bank managements showed "lax
morals, no control, lack of understanding, little attention to
detail, inability to stimulate staff."
</P>
<P>
One of the greatest risks was the disruption that would be
caused if the introduction of the single European currency named
euro were to be delayed or canceled.
</P>
<P>
"The risk of bungled or premature EMU is rising," said Sir Adam
Ridley of Hambros Bank. Some other respondents also warned that
the EMU would increase the pressure for rationalization in the
French and Italian banking sectors.
</P>
<P>
Another primary concern for the bankers was excessive
competition, as surplus capital would drive banks to chase riskier
lending or trade in less liquid securities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
