<DOCNO> XIE19970403.0288 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major Refuses to Rule Out Britain's EMU Membership </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 2 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister John Major
has flatly refused to rule out his country's membership of the
European Monetary Union (EMU), saying that he would not "play
partisan politics."
</P>
<P>
Speaking in a BBC radio interview today, Major, who is under
growing pressure to take a tougher line on the single currency,
said that the British government should take part in various
debates on the EMU as a single currency would affect Britain no
matter it would join it or not.
</P>
<P>
"And that is why as prime minister, with the interests of the
British nation as a whole at stake, I am not prepared to play
partisan politics. I must be there to represent the British
interest," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said, "Let us suppose the other nations went ahead with the
European currency on a weak basis and produced a weak euro. What
would happen is that all the money that flows into Europe would
flow into the two strong currencies, let us say the Swiss franc
and sterling."
</P>
<P>
"That would put up exchange rate of sterling, damage our
exports and cost us jobs. That is a matter of very direct
relevance to us, whether we are in a single currency or whether we
are not in a single currency," he added.
</P>
<P>
The British government, which negotiated an "opt-out" right on
the single currency, has made it clear that "it is very unlikely
that a single currency can proceed safely on January 1, 1999, but
even if it did proceed with unreliable convergence, Britain would
not be part of it." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
