<HEADLINE> King Hussein Discusses Mideast Situation With Albright </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 2 (Xinhua) -- King Hussein of Jordan
discussed the volatile situation in the Middle East with U.S.
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright in the State Department
today, State Department spokesman Nicholas Burns said.
</P>
<P>
The discussions between the king and the secretary of state,
who also attended a White House meeting between the king and
President Bill Clinton Tuesday, were "designed to help the United
States play a constructive role in bringing the Israelis and
Palestinians together so that we might help them repair some of
the damage caused over the last couple of weeks by a variety of
events," Burns told reporters at a regular briefing.
</P>
<P>
Clinton, after his meeting with King Hussein Tuesday, said he
was "personally prepared to do anything I can" to get peace talks
between the Israelis and Palestinians back on track.
</P>
<P>
He is looking forward to meeting Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu next week in an attempt to salvage the almost
broken down peace process. Netanyahu was reported to come to
Washington.
</P>
<P>
"We're pleased he's coming, and we're looking forward to
productive talks with him" when he meets with President Clinton
and Secretary Albright, Burns said.
</P>
<P>
He said Netanyahu's visit to Washington next Monday was
"important... particularly now that the peace negotiations are in
such dire straits."
</P>
<P>
"What we have in mind is using the influence of the United
States and the leadership of the president and the secretary of
state to... help the Israelis and Palestinians overcome their
differences," he said.
</P>
<P>
At the White House, press secretary Mike McCurry brushed aside
questions about a possible Middle East summit, saying he was
unaware of plans for such a gathering "right now."
</P>
<P>
"We've explored a number of ideas on how we can get the parties
to re-engage," McCurry said at a briefing. "I'm not aware of any
plans for a summit." 
</P>
</TEXT>
