<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French Gov't Optimistic About 1997 Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 2 (Xinhua) -- The French government today made an
optimistic prediction of the country's economic situation in 1997,
predicting a 2.3 percent growth and a public deficit controlled at
3 percent of the gross domestic product (GDP).
</P>
<P>
Minister of Finance and Economy Jean Arthuis said a 2.3 percent
growth is a "floor" and the government expects better economic
growth in the months to come.
</P>
<P>
The French national commission of account today also predicted
a 2.8 percent economic growth for the country in 1998. The
economic growth rate of France in 1996 was 1.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, eight big economic institutions of France made a
somewhat less optimistic prediction of the economy, predicting a
2.2 percent growth in 1997 and 2.6 percent for 1998.
</P>
<P>
The French government also predicts the creation of 120,000 to
140,000 jobs in 1997.
</P>
<P>
A total of 120,000 students graduate each year in France to
enter the country's job market.
</P>
<P>
The government said that France's exports will grow by 5.3
percent this year and will earn a surplus of 130 to 140 billion
francs (25 to 27 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The household purchase in France is expected to grow by 1.6
percent in 1997, lower than 2.1 percent in 1996, which was largely
attributed to the large quantity of automobiles bought by French
families taking advantage of a preferential policy by Prime
Minister Alain Juppe.
</P>
<P>
On the public deficit, the government said that it will be
controlled at 3 percent of the GDP, the criteria set by the
European Union for admitting to the European single currency,
euro, in 1999.
</P>
<P>
But French economic institutions predict the country's public
deficit at 3.1 percent of the GDP. 
</P>
</TEXT>
